<DOCNO> XIE19971115.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Satellite Launched by Chinese Rocket Passes In-Orbit Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 14 (Xinhua) -- A telecommunications
satellite launched by a Chinese rocket for APT Satellite Holdings
Limited, a Hong Kong-based major satellite operator in the
Asia-Pacific region, passed all the in-orbit tests today and will
commence commercial operations soon.
</P>
<P>
A reception was held today at Hong Kong's JW Marriot Hotel to
mark the successful launch of the APSTAR IIR satellite, which was
launched accurately into orbit on October 17 by the powerful Long
March 3B launch vehicle of the China Great Wall Industry
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The satellite was then successfully stationed at 76.5 degree
East Longitude on October 27. The in-orbit tests finished today
showed complete compliance with each prime specification and that
the satellite was ready for normal operation.
</P>
<P>
This was the third flight of the Long March-3B (LM-3B) rocket
and the second success since August of this year. Up to now, China
Great Wall Industry Corporation has signed 26 foreign launch
service agreements and successfully launched nine
telecommunication satellites.
</P>
<P>
APSTAR IIR is a high powered satellite manufactured by Space
Systems/Loral of the United States and has a mission life of 15
years.
</P>
<P>
The satellite has 28 C-band and 16 Ku-band transponders at TWTA
power level of 60W and 110W respectively.
</P>
<P>
Being equipped with high EIRP (equivalent isotropic radiated
power) value and the more reliable Ku-Band transponders, the
satellite is able to transmit TV programs directly to the densely
populated areas covered by the bandwidth, which lays the
foundation for future direct broadcasting satellite services.
</P>
<P>
APT Satellite Holdings Limited presently owns three in-orbit
telecommunications satellites, APSTAR I, APSTAR IA and APSTAR IIR,
altogether 92 transponders and provides satellite broadcasting
services to over 100 countries throughout most of Asia, Europe,
Africa and Australia, reaching approximately 75 percent of the
world's total population.
</P>
<P>
The Long March 3B (LM-3B) launch vehicle is the most powerful
of the Long March series and is capable of launching a payload of
up to five tons into geo-synchronous transfer orbit (GTO).
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR), attended the reception and extended
his congratulations to the three companies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
