<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India to Gradually Lift Restrictions Over EU Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 14 (Xinhua) -- India has agreed to gradually
lift import restrictions on the European Union (EU)'s
agricultural, industrial and textile products, a press release
said here today.
</P>
<P>
The settlement came as the culmination to negotiations between
the two sides after the EU requested mediation consultations under
the World Trade Organization (WTO) in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
India will phase out the restrictions over a six-year period
and a substantial number of EU's exports will be liberalized
within the first three years, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
"We are very satisfied with this settlement," said Leon
Brittan, vice-president of the EU's executive body European
Commission. He added that the settlement "represents a significant
improvement in market access for EU exporters and means EU
priority products are ensured early liberalization".
</P>
<P>
The EU is the main trading partner of India, which has
maintained import restrictions on a large number of products for
close to 40 years.
</P>
<P>
The EU-India trade in 1996 totalled 18.483 billion ECUs (about
24,000 million U.S. dollars), representing a growth of 85.3
percent since 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
