<DOCNO> XIE19971115.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Economists Stand for Linked Currency System: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 14 (Xinhua) -- A number of Hong Kong
economists stand for maintaining the linked exchange rate system
between the HK dollar and the U.S. dollar, Financial Secretary of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region's (SAR) government
Donald Tsang said today.
</P>
<P>
After his two-hour meeting with a group of senior academic
experts here, Tsang told reporters that the 10 economists believed
that maintaining the link would not only be instrumental to the
SAR's future growth and in fact would enhance its competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
"We have a very good exchange, two hours. They gave me a lot of
very interesting ideas," he said. "But one thing which is quite
unanimous among our academics was that it was utterly important
from Hong Kong's position as an international financial center to
maintain the linked exchange rate system."
</P>
<P>
"They believed that we have the technology, we have the
expertise, we have the resources and the determination to defend
the link," Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the meeting focused on "the various
activities in the currency market and the turbulence in the
currency market" in Hong Kong and the Southeast Asia as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that they mainly discussed whether the
SAR government needs to defend the 14-year-old linked exchange
rate system and how it may stabilize the local stock market facing
challenges from international speculators.
</P>
<P>
Tsang also told reporters that his colleagues will discuss in
details with the economists the "technical matters" including the
"currency board system" and "the way for dealing with the
speculators."
</P>
<P>
Since the turbulence occurred in the local stock market in late
October, the SAR government has repeatedly voiced its
determination to defend the peg system between the HK dollar and
U.S. dollar and described the SAR's economic fundamentals as good.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
