<HEADLINE> Clinton Orders Second Carrier to Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 14 (Xinhua) -- Amid rising tensions with
Iraq after Baghdad expelled American inspectors, U.S. President
Bill Clinton today ordered the aircraft carrier George Washington
to leave the Mediterranean for the Persian Gulf to join the
aircraft carrier Nimitz, already deployed there.
</P>
<P>
"I thought it was appropriate under the circumstances," Clinton
said during a photo session with Mexican President Ernesto
Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the United Nations made the correct decision in
withdrawing all the U.N. weapons inspectors in protest against
President Saddam Hussein's order to expel American inspectors
within the U.N. weapons inspection teams.
</P>
<P>
"The real issue is how to stop Saddam Hussein from
reconstituting weapons of mass destruction," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the United States also supported the U.N. decision
to send a U-2 spy plane over Iraq this weekend. "Because if we're
not on the ground, it's important to be in the air," he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether the withdrawal of the U.N. inspectors meant the
Iraqis got his way, Clinton said it would be a mistake to say
that.
</P>
<P>
"If his objective is to lift the sanctions, he has undermined
that objective,," he said. "The sanctions will never be lifted as
long as he does not comply." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
