<DOCNO> XIE19971115.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pre-historic Caves Found in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 14 (Xinhua) -- Pre-historic caves and
paintings dating back to the Stone Age have been discovered in
Musakhail area of Balochistan Province, Pakistan Television (PTV)
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paintings, which are of the Stone Age and date from 2000 BC
to 12,000 BC, have been found in caves and rock-shelters in
Musakhail in Loralai District, northeastern Balochistan in the
Suleman Mountainous Range, PTV said.
</P>
<P>
The discovery was made by Archaeologist Fazal Dad Kakar during
an archaeological survey in Balochistan province, it said.
</P>
<P>
The subject matter of Musakhail paintings is about animals, it
said, adding prominently displayed are wolfs, horses, bulls and
some human figures.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Musakhail caves and paintings are adding
new dimensions regionally, nationally and internationally to the
pre-historic discoveries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971115.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Producer Prices Pick Up in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. producer prices
rose by slight 0.1 percent in October, indicating that inflation
at the wholesale level nearly disappeared, the Labor Department
reported here today.
</P>
<P>
Prices paid for finished goods to producers such as food
processing plants and auto factories inched just 0.1 percent
higher, according to the department.
</P>
<P>
The monthly situation follows a sharp 0.5 percent jump in
September and a moderate 0.3 percent rise in August. The increases
came after seven consecutive declines, a post World War II record.
</P>
<P>
The Producer Price Index has declined at a 1.2 percent annual
rate for the first 10 months of this year, compared with a 2.8
percent increase during all of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Inflation has remained remarkably low this year, despite robust
growth and the lowest unemployment in 24 years. Some economic
analysts are predicting the financial chaos in Southeast Asia will
work to contain the prices of some commodities and goods next
year.
</P>
<P>
The Consumer Price Index, which includes service costs in
addition to retail goods prices, hasn't actually fallen, because
it more fully reflects rising wages. But it's increased at an
annual rate of just 1.8 percent through September.
</P>
<P>
Generally speaking, the wholesale level has recorded a sharp
decline in energy costs from January through May. However, even
excluding volatile food and energy costs, the producer index for
finished goods increased at only a 0.3 percent annual rate through
October, compared with a 0.6 percent increase for all of last
year.
</P>
<P>
In October, prices excluding food and energy were unchanged.
The seasonally adjusted price of new cars shot up 0.7 percent, but
prices fell for trucks, footwear and health products.
</P>
<P>
Energy costs rose only 0.1 percent in October. Gasoline fell
3.6 percent, but heating oil rose 2.1 percent; residential natural
gas, 2.9 percent, and electric power, 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Food prices rose 0.4 percent. Vegetables soared 16.8 percent,
with cauliflower up 269.7 percent and broccoli 108.1 percent.
Fruit prices rose 4.2 percent, pushed by a 63.2 percent increase
in raspberries and a 20.6 percent jump in table grapes.
</P>
<P>
But eggs fell 10 percent; pork 6.4 percent, the most in nearly
a decade; chicken 1.3 percent, and beef and veal 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, intermediate prices rose 0.3 percent and crude goods
costs 0.6 percent, mostly because of big jumps in natural gas and
crude petroleum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971115.0016 </DOCNO>
