<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Delegation Ends Visit to DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, November 13 (Xinhua) -- A Japanese official
delegation left Pyongyang for home today after reaching an
agreement with the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) on
resuming normalization talks, reported the Central Korean News
Agency (KCNA).
</P>
<P>
Both sides have expressed the wish to resume the talks as soon
as possible, said the official KCNA. Previous talks collapsed in
1992.
</P>
<P>
Japanese and DPRK people can advance together toward the future
while promoting understanding of each other, said Yoshiro Mori,
head of the delegation composed of the Japanese tripartite ruling
bloc, on the eve of his departure.
</P>
<P>
The talks between the ruling parties of the two countries will
provide a good opportunity for deepening understanding of the two
peoples and improving DPRK-Japanese relations, said Kim Yanggon, a
senior official of the DPRK's Workers' Party of Korea.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese delegation is composed of officials from the
Liberal Democratic Party, which is led by Japanese Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto, and its two allies -- the Social Democratic
Party and New Party Sakigake. It is the first Japanese official
mission dispatched to Pyongyang in two and a half years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
