<HEADLINE> UK Government Invests in Rolls Royce's New Engines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 14 (Xinhua) -- The British Government provided
200 million pounds (320 million US dollars) in financial support
to Rolls-Royce to help develop a new generation of aero engines.
</P>
<P>
The decision was seen as an encouraging pointer to British
Aerospace's plea for a contribution towards the cost of providing
the wings for a longer-range version of the A340.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the investment, John Battle, the industry minister,
said Thursday that the money was being advanced as a long-term
investment on which the government expected to earn "a commercial
rate of return."
</P>
<P>
The long term investment over the next four years to
Rolls-Royce plc towards the design and development of their
important new range of Trent engines will extend the Trent family
to enable to power all of the world's new large aircraft, Battle
said.
</P>
<P>
The Trent 500 has been selected by Airbus Industrie as the
power plant for the new A340-500/600, in a privileged partnership
announced at the Pair Air Show in June 1997.
</P>
<P>
It is believed here that the government's support reflects the
importance of this project to the UK economy and the clearly
established need for public funds to enable it to go ahead.
</P>
<P>
However, Battle said that the taxpayer should receive a rate of
return comparable with what the company will earn from the engine.
</P>
<P>
It was reported the minister is also discussing the help for
Rolls with the European Union but feels it comfortably meets the
rules covering state investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971115.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singaporean Official speaks of Financial Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, November 14 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's financial
deregulation plans will be based more on American and European
experience than on Japan's model, Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien
Loong, who heads Singapore's financial sector review committee,
said today.
</P>
<P>
At the end of his five-day working visit to Japan, Lee Hsien
Loong told the local media that his trip gave him some insight
into the Japanese financial reform, the local TV stations
reported.
</P>
<P>
Lee was briefed by Japanese Vice Minister of Finance Eisuke
Sakakibara on Japan's financial deregulation during the visit.
</P>
<P>
Lee said early this month that Singapore would review its
financial services sector, stressing that with the industry in a
stronger position to take risks, the emphasis should shift from
regulation to supervision that would deal differently with good
and bad institutions.
</P>
<P>
The proposed financial sector reform would be carried out not
in a big bang way, but more as a series of thunderclaps beginning
next year, he said last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Before winding up his Japan trip, Lee said that Singapore is
studying some Japanese reform such as allowing cross activities
and loosening control on fee and payment structures.
</P>
<P>
But overall, he said he felt Japan's situation is different
from Singapore's as the Japanese financial system is much bigger
and more regulated.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, American and European financial sector changes are
more relevant as they are more technological than regulatory in
nature.
</P>
<P>
Particularly noteworthy, Lee said, is the structural changes
resulting from the banking and financial institution mergers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
