<DOCNO> XIE19971115.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Retail Sales Drop 0.2 Percent in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. retail sales went
down by a 0.2 percent in October, the second monthly straight
decline, the Commerce Department said here today.
</P>
<P>
The department noted that sales totaled a seasonally adjusted
213.7 billion dollars, as compared with 214.1 billion dollars in
September. But excluding the drop in autos, sales were up 0.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
Sales in September were revised from an initially reported 0.3
percent advance to a 0.1 percent decline. From June to August,
sales had risen for three months.
</P>
<P>
Retail sales account for about one-third of the nation's
economic activity, and the recent sluggishness has caused some
concern over how robust the holiday shopping season will be. The
Christmas season often accounts for half of a retailer's earnings.
</P>
<P>
According to the department reports, sales of durable goods,
items such as furnaces and furniture expected to last more than
three years, plunged 0.9 percent after falling 0.8 percent a month
earlier.
</P>
<P>
Auto dealers also witnessed a 2 percent drop following a 1.4
percent decline in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
There was similar situation in other durable goods categories
as well. Sales of building materials and hardware were down 0.1
percent, while purchases of furniture and other home furnishings
were flat.
</P>
<P>
However, nondurable goods such as food and fuel managed a 0.2
percent gain on top of a 0.4 percent advance in September.
</P>
<P>
Department stores recorded a 1.1 percent increase, erasing a
0.4 percent dip a month earlier. Clothing store sales increased
0.9 percent, as against September's 1.9 percent drop.
</P>
<P>
Purchases at grocery stores were up 0.3 percent following a 0.7
percent gain a month earlier. Gasoline station sales rose 0.4
percent after a 1.5 percent increase the previous month. Drug
store sales advanced 0.7 percent, slower than the 1.3 percent gain
in September. But checks at restaurants and bars were off 0.3
percent following a 1.4 percent increase a month earlier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971115.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Britain Moves to Exert More Pressure on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 14 (Xinhua) -- Britain stepped up its pressure
upon Iraq today by putting some British planes on alert as Prime
Minister Tony Blair warned the Iraqi government would make a
"severe mistake" if it continued to defy the international
community.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Armed Forces Minister John Reid announced in
parliament that the government would put a squadron of RAF Harrier
jets on a 48-hour alert as a "sensible precautionary measure."
</P>
<P>
This is the latest British military move following British
Defense Secretary George Robertson's announcement Thursday that
the British aircraft carrier Invincible would be sent to the
Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
The crisis between the United Nations and Iraq continued
worsening when Baghdad ordered Thursday all American arms
inspectors of the UN Special Commission on Iraq to leave the
country immediately.
</P>
<P>
Although Reid said no decision had yet been taken to send
either the RAF planes or the aircraft carrier Invincible to the
Gulf, local political analysts said that both moves were seen as
part of preparations to back any possible U.S. military action
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"Force is not ruled out, of course. We are not ruling out any
options including the military option but we hope for a diplomatic
solution," Reid said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Prime Minister Blair reaffirmed Britain's tough
stance towards the Iraqi government by saying that he wanted to
"make it absolutely clear to Saddam Hussein that he must come back
in line with Security Council resolutions."
</P>
<P>
"If he doesn't, then he's going to make a very, very severe
mistake indeed," Blair said. Downing Street sources said that
Blair would have a telephone conversation with U.S. President Bill
Clinton later this evening to review the latest situation.
</P>
<P>
Early this morning, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook held
talks with visiting U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright in
Edinburgh to discuss the latest development of the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
Albright told reporters after the meeting that she had been
told Britain "is beefing up its forces in the Gulf" and they also
discussed measures "in which we could increase the pressure on
Saddam Hussein."
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, Cook, who expressed his country's
solidarity with the Americans, said that he still hoped a
diplomatic solution could be found despite the "grave" situation.
</P>
<P>
"There will be a future round of intensive diplomacy," Cook
said. "There is a sense of urgency. All options are open." 
</P>
</TEXT>
