<HEADLINE> Heart Checks Urged for Diet Pills Users in US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 14 (Xinhua) -- Millions of Americans who
have taken fen-phen or Redux should get medical checkup now to see
if they develop symptoms of heart trouble, U.S. federal health
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Even if they feel fine, dieters who took the diet drugs at any
time should go to their doctor, according to recommendations
issued Thursday by the Food and Drug Administration, the National
Institutes of Health and the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention.
</P>
<P>
The new advice comes two months after fenfluramine -- the "fen"
in the diet drug combination fen-phen -- and Redux were pulled
from the market because they had been linked to potentially deadly
heart valve damage.
</P>
<P>
Since 1995, 14 million prescriptions have been written for
fenfluramine or Redux, mostly for women. The government estimates
between 1.2 million and 4.7 million Americans have taken the
drugs.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary evidence from five surveys indicates that about 30
percent of those who used the drugs had heart valve abnormalities,
although most had no symptoms.
</P>
<P>
The government now has reports of at least 132 people who have
taken fenfluramine or Redux and have valve deformities. FDA
surveys suggest 30 percent of dieters with no symptoms might have
valve damage.
</P>
<P>
The new guidelines are an attempt to quell confusion until the
government learns more about fenfluramine and Redux, said Dr.
Murray Lumpkin of the FDA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971115.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to Publish New Highway Code in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 14 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Department of
Environment and Transport said that it is updating the country's
Highway Code to reflect current traffic practices and new concerns
about road safety.
</P>
<P>
Local media reports today said that a final version of the new
code will be published in the middle of next year to replace the
current one which was revamped in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The new code will spell out the dangers of using a hand-held
telephone and warn against being distracted by a hands-free set.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Road Safety Baroness Hayman said, "No one is
saying that you can't have a mobile phone in your car. It can be a
life-saver. It's how and when you use it that is important."
</P>
<P>
She warned that the government did not rule out the possibility
of legislation to ban using mobile phones while driving.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, drivers who argue with their passengers, fiddle with
the radio or eat a sandwich while driving on the road will also be
in breach of the new code.
</P>
<P>
Hayman, who is consulting the industry and motoring
organizations about the new code, said that she hoped the proposed
changes would make the code easier to follow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
