<HEADLINE> Developing Countries Urged to Look for New Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 14 (Xinhua) -- The developing countries
should look for other sources of finance to support their
population programs in the face of dwindling funding from
traditional donor countries, a U.N. official said today.
</P>
<P>
Executive Director of the U.N. Population Fund (UNFPA) Nafis
Sadik told a press briefing here that some donor countries were
facing budget problems and had advised they would be cutting
their aid to the body.
</P>
<P>
"Japan, which is one of our biggest financiers, has just
announced that it is having budget problems because of the
situation on the international financial markets and would not be
able to continue providing funds for us," she said.
</P>
<P>
Sadik, who is in the country to attend the UNFPA Africa
Division Regional Meeting underway in Harare, said the meeting
would discuss how member countries could mobilize resources to
fund their population programs.
</P>
<P>
"We need to mobilize resources from bilateral donors at
country level and hope that the world bank will increase its
support of population programs," she said.
</P>
<P>
She hoped some developing countries in the Africa, Caribbean and
pacific bloc, which had included population issues in their proposals
for a new trade agreement with the European Union after expiry of the
Lome Convention in 2000, could secure funding from the union.
</P>
<P>
The meeting would also discuss progress on the implementation of
recommendations of the Cairo Population Conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
