<HEADLINE> Mkapa Re-elected as Tanzanian Party Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, November 14 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa was re-elected Thursday night as the national
chairman of the ruling Revolutionary Party of Tanzania (CCM) for
another five-year term in the new capital of Dodoma.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa, 59, scooped 1,464 votes out of 1,475 votes cast,
equivalent to 99.25 percent of all votes cast. One vote was
invalid and 10 delegates voted against, said conference chairman
Alhaj Ali Hassan Mwinyi.
</P>
<P>
Also re-elected were John Malecela as vice-chairman for the
Tanzanian mainland and Salmin Amour as vice-chairman for
Zanzibar. Malecela got 1,469 votes out of 1,478 votes cast,
Salmin Amour netted 1,475 out of 1,483.
</P>
<P>
New seats of the National Executive Committee, 20 for the
Tanzanian mainland, 20 for Zanzibar, 15 for women, 10 for youths
and five for parents, were not announced until in the early hours
of Friday.
</P>
<P>
CCM, known as the Revolutionary Party, was founded on February
5, 1977. 
</P>
</TEXT>
