<HEADLINE> Mugabe Laments Erosion of Zimbabwean Culture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 14 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe today expressed disappointment at the low level of
government support for arts, saying this was contributing to the
alienation of the Zimbabwean culture.
</P>
<P>
He was officially opening the Zimbabwe Heritage Exhibition '97
at the National Art Gallery in Bulawayo, the country's second
largest city.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said there was a tendency to treat cultural activities
as mere appendages to big social programs, thereby providing the
sector with meager resources.
</P>
<P>
As a post independent society, Zimbabweans continue to suffer
a "wound in the soul", as the long-term effect of cultural
debasement which colonialism contrived in order to facilitate
their subjugation.
</P>
<P>
He said, "the renowned Zimbabwean poet, Musayemura Zimunya, at
one point rightly described the indigenous people of this country
as cultural hollow men and women."
</P>
<P>
Pledging financial support for the development arts, the
president said, "it is only through a combined effort of our
population sectors that the future of both visual and performing
arts can be secured."
</P>
<P>
Efforts were underway to make art more easily accessible to a
wider spectrum of communities by decentralizing the national gallery,
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
