<DOCNO> XIE19971115.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Currency Drops to Record Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 14 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's financial market
was today on the verge of collapse after the local currency
Zimbabwean Dollar (ZD) plummeted to a record low due to panic
importer demand of the U.S. Dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe (RBZ) had to intervene in the
foreign exchange market to raise the Zimbabwean Dollar from an
all time low of 25 Zimbabwean Dollars before recovering to about
17 Zimbabwean Dollars to one U.S. Dollar compared with Thursday's
closing of 14.25 Zimbabwean Dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Currency traders say they have seen huge importer demand
because the RBZ is short on reserves and is limited in the way it
can intervene. This has led to panic importation," said Sagit
stock brokers in an interview with the Zimbabwe News Agency.
</P>
<P>
There have been rumors in recent days that Zimbabwe's foreign
currency had fallen to below two month's worth of imports.
</P>
<P>
Noted economist Joseph Muzulu attributed the depreciation to
importer demand, speculation and the fact that there was little
progress with regards to balance of payments support from the
World Bank.
</P>
<P>
He said speculation in the market that the Zimbabwean Dollar
would continue to depreciate and importers would benefit more if
they waited was also a contributory factor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
