<HEADLINE> Iraq Seeks Dialogue with Security Council: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 14 (Xinhua) -- Iraq today urged the U.N.
Security Council to stop repeating American rhetoric and start
serious dialogue with Iraq to solve the current crisis over
weapons monitoring.
</P>
<P>
"It is useful, proper and logical to discuss how to start real
and serious dialogue with Iraq," Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed
Saeed al-Sahhaf said at a press conference here Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
In a less upbeat tone, the foreign minister reiterated that
Iraq "seeks no confrontation with anybody," but a dialogue, even
with the United States.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has taken the position that it was ready for serious
political dialogue with the U.S. without any preconditions since
April 1991 and it has maintained its position, al-Sahhaf said.
</P>
<P>
"This is the only way which can be used by Iraq and the U.S. to
solve their differences," he said, adding a dialogue does not mean
Iraq backs off from its demands regarding the lifting of the
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Iraq wants "its concerns and grievances heard and a dialogue
opened" to get rid of the seven-year-old crippling U.N. sanctions,
he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
He rebuffed accusations that Iraq is trying to make use of the
current suspension of U.N. weapons inspection to produce
biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
The factories, labs and equipment under monitoring are
categorized as "of dual use" and are not capable of churn out
prohibited materials, and it takes months to produce biological
agents, as known to experts, he explained.
</P>
<P>
He said the Iraqi people, who gathered in presidential palaces
of Saddam Hussein to form human shields in an attempt to fend off
possible military actions, have now been around and inside many
factories, palaces, industrial compounds.
</P>
<P>
The forming of human shields has become a popular movement all
over the country, he added.
</P>
<P>
The press conference came after U.S. President Bill Clinton
confirmed that aircraft carrier George Washington has been ordered
to join another aircraft carrier Nimitz in the Persian Gulf,
apparently to brace for possible conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The two-week-old standoff between Iraq and U.S. and UNSCOM,
which oversees elimination of Iraq's weapons of mass destruction
is possibly coming to a showdown. Baghdad expelled six Americans
on the U.N. inspection teams hours after the Security Council
passed a resolution Thursday condemning Iraq's non-compliance and
interference in inspection missions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
