<HEADLINE> OAU Backs Africa Development: Salim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, November 14 (xinhua) -- The OAU is deploying all
efforts aimed at supporting its member states in meeting the
formidable challenges of socio-economic development and progress
in conditions of peace and democracy, The OAU chief said today.
</P>
<P>
 The remarks were made by Secretary General of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) Salim Ahmed Salim when he
addressed a meeting at the U.N. conference center here.
</P>
<P>
Salim said, ''we are fully committed to promoting economic
development, cooperation and integration in the continent and to
establishing the African economic community as the most viable
framework for such development.''
</P>
<P>
He further said OAU has been cognizant of the need to work
together and to build a solid partnership with all organizations
and institutions concerned with the destiny of the African
continent and its peoples.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is attended by over 300 representatives of the
three million Rotarians in 29 different countries who have
arrived in Ethiopia to lend their services in the polio
immunization campaign which targeted 8.5 million children under
the age of five.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the meeting, President of Rotary International Glen
Kinross stressed the need to mount a global assault on poverty,
hunger, illiteracy and diseases.
</P>
<P>
He said, some 100 million children make their homes on the
streets of the world's cities, struggling to survive in desperate
conditions, adding that an estimated 900 million people do not
have the literacy and numeracy skills in the world.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the meeting, Ethiopian Speaker of the House of the
People's Representatives Dawit Yohannes said the Ethiopian
government's main agenda is to ensure the economic development of
the country, and it is well aware that building a prosperous,
self-reliant society can never be achieved without guaranteeing
the Ethiopian child.
</P>
<P>
As children mean Ethiopia's tomorrow, he said, they should
have a healthy and promising environment and are "protected from
polio and other child killer diseases.''
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia yesterday launched its first nation-wide immunization
days against polio. 
</P>
</TEXT>
