<HEADLINE> Germany to Face New Bankruptcy Record in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 14 (Xinhua) -- The bankruptcy wave in Germany is
set to hit a new high in Germany in 1997, the German Federal
Statistics Office said today.
</P>
<P>
In the first eight months of this year, the number of
bankruptcy applications in Germany totaled 22,135, an increase of
6.4 percent over the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
In August alone, there were 2,772 applications for bankruptcy,
up 9.6 percent from the same month of 1996.
</P>
<P>
"If such a trend continues, a new record can be reached this
year," a spokesman of the Wiesbaden-based statistics office said.
</P>
<P>
According to an earlier projection of the office, the
bankruptcy total is expected to increase from 31,471 last year to
more than 32,000 by the end of 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
