<HEADLINE> Government Slams Turkish Visit to Northern Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, November 14 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government today
condemned a forthcoming visit by Turkey's Deputy Prime Minister
Bulent Ecevit to the northern areas of the island occupied by
Turkish troops.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit will be on the island Saturday with Turkish Foreign
Minister Ismail Cem to participate in "celebrations" marking the
15th anniversary of the establishment of "Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus" recognized only by Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash declared the breakaway
state in November 1983, a move the U.N. Security Council
described as "legally invalid."
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Manolis Christofides said in his daily
news briefing that Ecevit "has returned to the scene of his crime
and (this) proves that crimes committed in Cyprus against
international law and order are carried out by Turkey."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Greek Cypriot students in Nicosia took to the
streets today to protest against continuing Turkish occupation and
formation of the regime in northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
A petition adopted by the students calls on the five permanent
members of the U.N. Security Council to exercise their influence
on Turkey "to change its intransigent stand and pave the way for
the reunification of Cyprus and its people."
</P>
<P>
Christofides said the government expected the protest rallies,
which it endorses and approves, to be within the bounds of
legality.
</P>
<P>
The police have taken strict security measures to avert any
incidents.
</P>
<P>
The eastern Mediterranean island has been divided since 1974
when Turkey landed its troops and took over the northern third of
the island in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup seeking union
with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
