<HEADLINE> Local People Suffer From Floods in Southern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, November 14 (Xinhua) -- Apart from human and
livestock fatalities, the floods that hit seven regions of
southern Somalia are also bringing about starvation and famine in
many flood-besieged villages and towns.
</P>
<P>
In Gedo, Middle Jubba, Lower Jubba, Middle Shabelle, Hiran,
Bay and Bakol regions of southern Somalia, life has become
difficult for hundreds of thousands of people in the flood
affected towns and villages as the food prices rose to five
folds.
</P>
<P>
The communication problems created by the floods are
sharpening not only the prices of the locally produced food items
but also the prices of imported rice and spaghettini.
</P>
<P>
These communication hindrances are also affecting the capital
Mogadishu with an increase of more than 50% in the prices of the
coal used for the cooking, milk, vegetables and butter which come
from these regions.
</P>
<P>
These disasters are taking place at a time when Somalia's
faction leaders are meeting in Cairo for a possible solution to
the long-standing political crises in the country which also made
it difficult for the international community to easily tackle the
flood problems in Somalia. 
</P>
