<HEADLINE> Siemens Takes Over Westinghouse's Power Generation Unit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 14 (Xinhua) -- Germany's electrical engineering
group Siemens AG announced today that it has acquired the
fossil-fueled power generation operations of the U.S. Westinghouse
group at a cost of 1.525 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
An agreement on the deal had been reached by the two companies
today, Siemens said, adding that the takeover had still to be
approved by anti-trust authorities in the United States and
Europe.
</P>
<P>
Based in Orlando, the United States, the Power Generation
Business Unit of the Industries and Technology Group of
Westinghouse has a work force of about 8,000 and is an active
supplier in the international markets for gas turbine,
combined-cycle and steam power plants.
</P>
<P>
By acquiring the Westinghouse unit, Siemens, which currently
has an 11 percent share of the world market in fossil-fueled power
generation, will be able to outstrip the Swedish-Swiss group ABB
as the world's No. 2 in power generation business after the U.S.
General Electric (GE).
</P>
<P>
Westinghouse, once the second largest U.S. electrical group
after th GE, has been transforming itself into one of the leading
U.S. media companies in recent years after its acquisition of the
media giant CBS.
</P>
<P>
The last remaining industrial business of Westinghouse, namely
its nuclear power generation operations, would also be sold by
mid-1998, the company announced today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
