<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Butler Hopes Inspectors Back to Iraq Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 14 (Xinhua) -- Richard Butler, chief
weapons inspector of the United Nations, said today he believed
U.N. inspectors, now pulled out of Iraq, would be back to
discharge their duties again.
</P>
<P>
"I refuse to believe that the international community is simply
going to walk away from the very large problem that is presented
by Iraq's weapons of mass destruction," he said in an interview
with CNN. "We'll have to be back, in one way or another, and as
soon as possible."
</P>
<P>
Six American inspectors of the U.N. weapons inspection teams
left Iraq late Thursday following Baghdad's order of their
expulsion. And the other 68 U.N. team members also flew out of
Iraq Friday to Bahrein under the order of Butler in protest to
Iraq's expulsion of the Americans.
</P>
<P>
Butler said Iraq might be engaging in "dangerous and illegal"
activities in the absence of the U.N. weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
"We can't see exactly what's happening now in the way that we
could before, and so of course we are concerned with our backs...
that activities may be taking place that are dangerous and
illegal," he told CNN.
</P>
<P>
There are still seven U.N. staff staying in Baghdad, guarding
equipment in a monitoring center there and 12 Chileans who fly and
service U.N. helicopters.
</P>
<P>
Butler said the flights of U-2 spy planes would be more
important now with no inspectors on ground in Iraq. He emphasized
that while U-2 planes were U.S.-made and piloted, they were under
the jurisdiction of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqis have said they would shoot down U-2 once found
flying over their territorial air. And the United States has vowed
to take retaliation if the Iraqis try to do so.
</P>
<P>
Butler hoped that the United Nations would take even greater
economic sanctions as the next step of warning. He said the new
punitive measure should "hit the spot."
</P>
<P>
"Sanctions are tough, they already are, and who knows, maybe
the (Security) Council will decide that more are required.
Whatever they decide it will have to be something that hits the
spot," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said it was necessary to "find a way to bring Iraq back to
its senses... and to get our monitors and inspectors back in the
country." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971115.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Militias Accused of Breaching Ceasefire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 14 (Xinhua) -- The military junta in Sierra
Leone, which is opposed to the disarmament of the armed forces,
has accused the hunter militias known as Kamajors of violating
ceasefire under a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Junta spokesman Aliu Kamara today claimed the Kamajors have
kept harassing civilians and vehicles as well as burning down
houses in the southeast of the country.
</P>
<P>
They are trying to capture a town in that area as their base
to fight against the junta, the spokesman told the British
Broadcasting Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The Kamajors used to be hunters in the hinterland and have
fought for the restoration of President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah since
he was deposed in the May 25 coup this year.
</P>
<P>
Repeated clashes were reported between the Kamajors and the
junta forces before the peace agreement was signed in Conakry,
Guinea, last month, which calls for ceasefire in that country.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, all people with guns, including
the Kamajors and the national army, will be disarmed and
President Kabbah is supposed to be reinstated in April next year.
</P>
<P>
The accusation came after the junta refused the demand of the
west African peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG for the
disarmament of the country's armed forces.
</P>
<P>
The junta and ECOMOG held a two-day meeting near the capital
Freetown to search for modalities to implement the peace plan.
</P>
<P>
But the smooth development of the peace process suffered
setback as the two parties differed as to who should be disarmed,
among other issues.
</P>
<P>
By accusing the Kamajors of breaking the ceasefire, Kamara
said the armed forces of Sierra Leone will not launch any
military operation to check it.
</P>
<P>
Instead, the junta is waiting to see how ECOMOG, which is
responsible for monitoring the ceasefire and disarmament in the
country according to the Conakry agreement, is going to deal with
the situation, the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
So far no response from ECOMOG is available.
</P>
<P>
However, a traveller back from southeastern Sierra Leone to
Freetown was quoted as confirming that the junta soldiers clashed
with the Kamajors starting on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"There has been no let-up since then, even as I left the area
on foot to join a vehicle at Kenema yesterday afternoon," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Aid agencies said there was heavy fighting at Ngigeahun, where
several houses have been torched, according to a report reaching
here today.
</P>
<P>
The Kamajors were rooted from the area in August by government
soldiers and former rebels now allied to the ruling junta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
