<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IGAD Appealed for Aid to Flood Victims in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, November 14 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-Governmental
Authority on Development (IGAD) has appealed for humanitarian
assistance to flood victims in southern Somalia.
</P>
<P>
According to an IGAD press release today, Kinfe Abraham,
director of political and humanitarian affairs of IGAD, said
after three weeks of disastrous flooding, international aid is
only now slowly reaching southern Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Aid agencies report that 450 people have drowned and 600
others are in imminent danger from rising waters, with 150,000
people displaced, 43 villages destroyed and 10,000 animals
killed.
</P>
<P>
The release said tens of thousands of hectares of land have
been inundated and 800,000 people are at risk of starvation and
diseases, particularly malaria and cholera.
</P>
<P>
Some of the victims are reportedly living in trees to escape
the crocodiles, snakes and other animals competing for food and
dry land.
</P>
<P>
"Despera`e appeals are being made by the aid agencies for
transport, equipment and skilled personnel to help hundreds of
thousands of Somalis who are displaced by the floods," the
release quoted the director as saying.
</P>
<P>
Roads have been swept away and relief workers are trying to
reach the victims with food and medicines, some of which are only
accessible by boats, the release said.
</P>
<P>
Since the region's airstrip has been submerged, the aid
agencies are appealing for helicopters, the release added.
</P>
<P>
Somalia is a member of IGAD which also includes Djibouti,
Eritrea, Ethiopia, Kenya, Uganda and the Sudan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
