<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Renews Appeal to US Congress for Payment of Dues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, November 14 (Xinhua)-- United Nations Secretary
General Kofi Annan today renewed his appeal to the U.S.
Republican-controlled Congress to approve the proposed payment of
American arrears to the world body.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing here, Annan said that he was
"disappointed" and "concerned" with the fact that the U.S.
Congress "did not act" on the legislation put forward by the
Clinton administration that "would have taken a significant step
toward funding the more than 1 billion U.S. dollars in overdue
U.S. payments to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"It is both unreasonable and regrettable that the legislation
was held hostage to the entirely unrelated domestic politics of
abortion," the U.N. chief said.
</P>
<P>
Annan said that the failure "comes during a week when the
United Nations Security Council had been seized by the crisis
regarding arms inspection in Iraq, in which the United Nations
plays a role that is indispensable to international peace and
security as well as to the vital national security interests of
the United States."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. owes a total of some 1.5 billion U.S. dollars to the
United Nations. The Clinton administration pledged that the U.S.
would first pay 1 billion U.S. dollars this year and the rest in
the next few years when Annan took the post early in the year.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the Organization was in a deep financial crisis,
the U.N. chief expressed the hope that the pledge of the Clinton
administration was still valid now.
</P>
<P>
Annan urged all member states to "take serious stock of our
financial vulnerabilities."
</P>
<P>
He said that he was asking the president of the U.N. General
Assembly to reconvene, as a matter of urgency, the Assembly's
high-level group on finance to explore all possible options for
ensuring prompt payment by member states of their dues, and to
report their recommendations before the end of the current session
of the Assembly." 
</P>
</TEXT>
