<HEADLINE> UN Security Council Tends Tajikistan Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, November 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council passed a resolution here today, encouraging Tajikistan to
make greater peace and reconstruction efforts and calling on the
international community to extend their helping hands.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, members of the Security Council agreed unanimously
to expand the U.N. Mission of Observers in Tajikistan (UNMOT),
since the security situation in the country remains "volatile
with, in particular, a high level of violence in the central part
of the country."
</P>
<P>
The road ahead will still be difficult for the country,
according to some representatives.
</P>
<P>
The council also decided to extend the mandate of the UNMOT
until May 15, 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to the resolution, the government of Tajikistan and
the United Tajik Opposition (UTO) are taking serious efforts to
carry out their commitments under the General Agreement on the
Establishment of Peace and National Accord in Tajikistan. They
also achieved some progress in the activities of the Commission on
National Reconciliation, the exchange of prisoners of war and
detainees, and repatriation of refugees.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the Chinese government, Chinese ambassador Qin
Huasun said that China appreciates the progress made by the
involving parties in the implementation of the General Agreement.
He said the General Agreement is conducive to promoting the
peaceful progress and realizing the final national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed China's appreciation for the efforts of
Secretary-General Kofi Annan, and Russia and other countries in
the region in their mediation efforts.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese representative, acting as the Security Council
chairman for this month, also called on the international
community to offer Tajikistan the much needed aid to help the
country to have quicker reconstruction of its economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
