<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt: Boycott of Doha Not to Affect Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 14 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's boycott of the Middle
East and North Africa (MENA) Economic Conference, due to open in
Qatari capital Doha Sunday, will not affect its relations with
Qatar, Egypt's ambassador to Doha Mohamad Meneissi said today.
</P>
<P>
Nor will it affect the treatment of Egyptians working in Qatar,
Meneissi told reporters shortly before leaving for Qatar at the
end of a week-long "vacation at home."
</P>
<P>
Meneissi said he was recalled by the Foreign Ministry back to
Cairo last weekend for consultations on means to restore the
"usual warmth in bilateral ties" with Qatar.
</P>
<P>
Their relationship was adversely affected by Egypt's criticism
of Qatar's insistence in holding the conference regardless
widespread Arab opposition, and by Qatar's decision to bar
Egyptian nationals from entering the country during the conference.
</P>
<P>
"The reason Egypt is boycotting the Doha conference is that
Israeli Premier Benjamin Netanyahu continues to refuse to listen
to the voice of reason and persists in his disregard for signed
agreements," Meneissi explained.
</P>
<P>
He said he met Foreign Minister Amr Moussa several times to
discuss ways to shore up Egypt-Qatar relations, adding he will
talk to Qatari "brothers" within the context of "continuous
understanding and consultation between the two sisterly countries"
in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador denied that Egyptian living in Qatar are the
targets of certain sort of harassment as a result of Egypt's
stance on the conference and that he is the subject of any press
campaign.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian ambassador ruled out Arab mediation to calm down
the situation between Egypt and Qatar. "The relationship between
the two countries is such that it would require no mediation
whatsoever," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said he does not expect much from the Doha conference in
light of the massive Arab boycott. Most Arab countries, including
Egypt and Saudi Arabia, refused to send their delegations to the
meeting which also includes Israel.
</P>
<P>
"The conference is being held at a time the intransigent
attitude of the Israeli government has hurled back the peace
process to zero point and wreaked havoc on the outcome of the
three economic conferences in Morocco, Jordan and Egypt,"
Meneissi added.
</P>
<P>
The boycott camp views the gathering as a reward to the
Netanyahu government's hardline policy, held responsible for
bogging down the Middle East peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
