<HEADLINE> EU Delegation Visits Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, November 14 (Xinhua) -- A European Union (EU)
delegation visited Lebanon today on the fifth leg of its Middle
East tour aimed at reviving the stalled peace talks and playing a
larger role in the region.
</P>
<P>
The delegation is led by Luxembourg Foreign Minister Jacques
Poos, whose country now holds the rotating EU presidency.
</P>
<P>
They held talks with Lebanese President Elias Hrawi and Foreign
Minister Fares Boueiz to discuss the regional situation,
especially in south Lebanon. The EU special envoy to the Middle
East Miguel Angel Moratinos was present at the meetings.
</P>
<P>
At a joint news conference after meeting with Boueiz, Poos told
reporters that their talks focused on two difficulties Lebanon is
facing - the Israeli occupation of south Lebanon and the 350,000
Palestinian refugees living in Lebanon, who make up one tenth of
the country's population.
</P>
<P>
"We reaffirm our support to the implementation of the
U.N. Security Council resolution 425 and demand Israel withdraw
from south Lebanon without any condition," Poos said.
</P>
<P>
Since 1985, Israeli troops carved out a 1,200-square-kilometer
enclave in south Lebanon along the common border to buffer
cross-border guerrilla attacks on its northern settlements.
</P>
<P>
Asked about proposed pressure on Israel, he said that if
pressure is used in tackling international affairs, it will only
bring negative results. The best way is through means of friendly
dialogue, he added.
</P>
<P>
As for the Palestinian refugees, he said a fair and lasting
peace couldn't be achieved if this problem is not resolved and any
solution to the problem should be based on the principles of
international laws.
</P>
<P>
Before arriving in Lebanon, Poos and his delegation visited
Egypt, Jordan, Israel and Palestinian self-rule areas and held
talks with their leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
