<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sierra Leone Situation Calls U.N. Attention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, November 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council condemned again today the military coup in Sierra Leone in
May, 1997, which overthrew President Ahmad Tejan Kabbah, and
pressed the junta to restore peace and a democratic government.
</P>
<P>
According to a presidential statement released here today, the
Security Council showed its concern about the threat caused by the
coup to peace, security and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
"The Security Council expressed its full support and
appreciation for the continued efforts of the Committee of Five on
Sierra Leone of the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS) to seek a peaceful settlement of the crisis and the
restoration of the democratically-elected government and
constitutional order," the statement says.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, it says, the Security Council welcomes the
peace plan agreed last month between the ECOWAS Committee and
representatives of the junta.
</P>
<P>
President Kabbah already accepted the peace plan in his
statement of November 5.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council also calls upon the junta to fulfil its
obligations under the peace plan, and in particular the ongoing
maintenance of the cease-fire, the statement says.
</P>
<P>
It reiterates the need for the provision and distribution of
humanitarian assistance in response to local needs, and calls upon
the junta to ensure its safe delivery to its intended recipients.
It urges all States and relevant international organizations to
continue to assist those countries dealing with the influx of
refugees caused by the crisis in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Security Council reminds in the statement all
states of their obligation to continue to comply strictly with the
embargo on the sale or supply of petroleum and petroleum products
and arms to Sierra Leone, in accordance to the relevant U.N.
resolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
