<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey: One Million U.S. Women Stalked Each Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 14 (Xinhua) -- More than one million women
in the United States are stalked every year and one out of every
12 women will be stalked at some point in their lives, a national
survey said.
</P>
<P>
The study released by the Justice Department Thursday also
reported that more than 370,000 men are stalked each year. The
majority of stalking victims of both sexes were between the ages
of 18 and 39. About 10 percent were under 18.
</P>
<P>
Of the stalking victims, 59 percent of women were stalked by
spouses, former spouses, live-in partners or dates, while 70
percent of men were stalked by "acquaintances" or strangers, the
study showed.
</P>
<P>
About half of the stalking victims told the police, the survey
said. And about 25 percent obtained restraining orders against the
stalker. One-quarter of the women who reported to the police said
the cases were prosecuted. Convictions were obtained in 54 percent
of the cases and 63 percent of the convictions resulted in jail
time, the study said.
</P>
<P>
The stalking data are part of a larger National Violence
Against Women survey being prepared by the Denver-based Center for
Policy Research, a private organization specializing in empirical
research on family violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
