<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Danish Wins OOCL Yachting Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 15 (Xinhua) -- After a tight-scheduled
final day, 1997 Oriental Overseas Container Line Ltd. (OOCL)
Etchells World Yachting Championships came to a close here on
Saturday, with Denmark's two-time Olympic champion Poul-Richard
Hoj-Jensen winning the top place of the final point standings.
</P>
<P>
But it was Australia's Noel Drennan, who won the trophy of the
three-year-long, four regatta OOCL World Series.
</P>
<P>
As Race 5 for Friday was postponed due to a lack of wind,
Saturday saw two races on the program.
</P>
<P>
The organizers were much worried as many of the overseas
sailors had booked air tickets for Sunday and only a light wind
was available today.
</P>
<P>
The 30-boat-strong, international fleet went out early today to
compete two shorter, nine miles races. Olympic bronze-medalist
Jeff Madrigali from the United States took the fifth race,
followed by Hoj-Jensen and another American Steve Wright.
</P>
<P>
It was Australian Colin Beashel, a two-time Etchells world
champion and America's Cup veteran, who finally had his first, in
Race 6. Hoj-Jensen was second again and Wright took another third.
</P>
<P>
After the sixth and final race, Hoj-Jensen was ranked atop the
final points standings, followed by Colin Beashel, Drennan,
Australia's America's Cup winner John Bertrand and Madrigali.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the organizing committee were lucky to get both
races completed, which guaranteed a on-time conclusion of the
World Championships.
</P>
<P>
However, Drennan, with his third overall in the OOCL World
Championships, second in the Hong Kong, China Championships
earlier this month, and second in the 1996 OOCL Fifth Asia Pacific
Championships, took away the OOCL World Series trophy. The OOCL
World Championships is the last leg ofthe World Series.
</P>
<P>
The world championships attracted a field of thirty boats and
91 sailors from six countries and regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
