<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian PM Ends Visit to Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Bosnian Prime Minister
Haris Silajdzic wrapped up his two-day official visit here today,
during which he held talks with Kuwait leaders on strengthening
ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said in an interview with local Kuwait news
agency Kuna before leaving "We wish to promote economic ties with
Kuwait as our political relations are already strong."
</P>
<P>
Kuwait and Bosnia have similarities as to geography, population
and military force, he said, expressing hope that superpowers
would restore security and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that the two countries have potential in further
developing economic and trade ties on an even footing, noting that
Bosnia is rich in its sufficient and skillful workforce as well as
natural resources.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Silajdzic held talks with Kuwaiti Amir
Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah and Crown Prince and Prime
Minister Sheikh Saad Al-Abdullah Al-Sabah.
</P>
<P>
He praised the positive and supportive stance of Kuwait to
Bosnia during the civil war in former Yugoslavia. The Kuwaiti
leaders, on their part, expressed thanks for his calling on Iraq
to comply with the U.N. resolutions adopted since it invaded
Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait was among the first countries to welcome the
independence of the republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina from the
former Yugoslavia in April 1992 and recognized it as an
independent state.
</P>
<P>
In January 1993, Kuwait and the Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina
announced the establishment of diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti cabinet of ministers last Wednesday expressed the hope
that Silajdzic's visit would contribute to substantiating the
"already deep-rooted relations" between the two friendly
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
