<HEADLINE> Philippines May Exit from IMF: IMF Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Chief of the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) Michel Camdessus said here today that he saw
no need to extend an IMF program for the Philippines despite
concerns that Manila failed to fulfill key conditions.
</P>
<P>
"I don't see any merit in extending the program," Camdessus
said at a press conference. He was in the country following visits
to Malaysia, Indonesia, Singapore and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The exit of the Philippines from the IMF tutelage is "not at
all a problem" since the IMF program is due to expire at the end
of this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines has been hoping to graduate from the IMF after
35 years of being put under the IMF economic stewardship.
</P>
<P>
However, its scheduled exit in December was put in doubt when
the country's Supreme Court announced an oil deregulation law
"unconstitutional".  
</P>
</TEXT>
