<HEADLINE> Bodies of Killed Americans Flown back from Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 15 (Xinhua) -- The bodies of the four
Americans who were killed Wednesday by unidentified gunmen in
Karachi, Pakistan's biggest city, were flown back today to the
United States, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The chartered Airbus flight No 993 of the Canadian Sky Services
which carried the bodies left Karachi, capital of Sindh province
for Maryland at about 3 p.m., the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Sindh Provincial Minister for Excise and Taxation Ismail Rahu,
U.S. Consul General Douglas B. Archard and other Pakistani
officials were present at the Karachi Airport to pay respect to
the bodies kept in coffins, they said.
</P>
<P>
The four Americans, who were employees of the Union Texas
Pakistan, were gunned down early Wednesday by the unidentified
gunmen near a five-star hotel in Karachi. No individual or group
has claimed responsibility for the incident so far.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's police and the Federal Bureau of Investigation have
launched joint probe into the killing incident but made no
significant headway.
</P>
<P>
The four Americans were killed one day after a U.S. court
sentenced Aimal Kansi, a Pakistani national who was charged of
killing two agents of the Central Intelligence Agency in January
1993.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
