<HEADLINE> Platinum Mining Giant Pledges to Hire Zimbabwean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Multi-national platinum mining
giant, BHP, today said there is an urgent need for quality
leaders in Zimbabwe and the company would therefore aggressively
promote the employment of university graduates at its mines.
</P>
<P>
BHP Zimbabwe Executive Director John Andersen told student
representatives from all the faculties at the University of
Zimbabwe that the company would next year offer sponsorship to
some university students in addition to industrial attachments.
</P>
<P>
''We have an urgent need for good quality leaders and the
university is the place to get them. Our graduate recruitment
will go ahead. It is an investment for the future,'' Andersen
said.
</P>
<P>
''We will be visiting the university to try and influence the
faculties on what we require,'' Andersen said at the one-day
careers guidance seminar in Harare which is also attended by
Anglo American Corporation Director Jonathan Oppenheimer who runs
the company's gold mines in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Andersen said BHP Zimbabwe, which has a multi-billion dollar
platinum mining venture at Selous, 80 km southwest of Harare, now
has a skilled work force of 3,150.
</P>
<P>
Guy Georgias, owner of Harare-based Trinity Engineering, one
of the major manufacturers of truck bodies and trailers in
Zimbabwe, also addressed the seminar and told the students that
they should cultivate a culture of initiating employment
opportunities for themselves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
