<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton dispatched an aircraft carrier to join
another already in the Persian Gulf in an attempt to signal that
the United States did not take lightly Iraq's expulsion of six
American members on an international weapons inspection team.
</P>
<P>
-- Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright had talks with
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of Israel in London, during
which she called on Israelis and Palestinians "to move on the
peace process." She will meet the Palestinian leader Yasir Arafat
on her way to a Middle Eastern economic conference in Qatar that
major Arab nations are boycotting.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- Congress's refusal to pay almost 1 billion dollars owed by
the United States to the United Nations hit here like a hurricane
today, unleashing fears that the world body will run out of money
in 1998 and all but sinking the Clinton administration's hopes of
getting the U.S.share of the U.N. budget reduced from 25 percent
to 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton signed Friday a 13.8 billion dollar
Interior Department appropriations bill that clinches a pair of
hard-fought environmental victories for the White House while also
expanding a number of federal timber programs bitterly opposed by
environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
Herald Tribune
</P>
<P>
-- While U.S.-led military action has succeeded before in
thwarting President Saddam Hussein of Iraq when diplomacy has
failed, the challenges raised by Saddam's defiance this time make
the use of force more problematic, according to administration
officials and outside specialists.
</P>
<P>
-- Secretary-General Kofi Annan assailed Congress and the
anti-abortion lobby in the United States on Friday for killing a
plan to pay the United Nations more than 1 billion dollars in back
dues, calling the vote "unreasonable and regrettable." 
</P>
</TEXT>
