<HEADLINE> Major Oil Companies Invest in North China City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Caltex, a major international
oil company, has invested 30 million U.S dollars to establish a
lubricant processing plant in Tianjin city in north China.
</P>
<P>
The plant, located in the Tianjin Port Bonded Area, will have
an annual production capacity of 60,000 tons of lubricants.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin, the largest industrial center in north China, has
emerged as a major channel for attracting transnational oil
producers to China's petrochemical market.
</P>
<P>
Mobil and Esso have invested over 30 million U.S. dollars each
in the city, with Shell investing 100 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
San Xiangjun, director of the Bonded Area Administrative
Committee, said Tianjing will develop a petrochemical zone
covering 30 square kilometers. He noted that investments from
major transnational oil companies will enable the zone to become
one of the country's petrochemical bases.
</P>
<P>
A dock to serve the petrochemical industry is currently under
construction in Tianjin port, according to San, with three berths
already completed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
