<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Hosts Enterprise Property Rights Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's First Enterprise
Property Rights Transfer Fair, the first of its kind in the
Chinese capital, attracted prospective buyers for some 56 small
industrial and service enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The total assets of related enterprises exceeded 600 million
yuan. Their assests vary from one million yuan to more than 10
million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The enterprises involved came from the machine-building,
chemical, textile, electronics, food processing and commercial
sectors in the suburban counties of Daxing, Miyun, Changping and
Huairou.
</P>
<P>
Said enterprises faced severe financial problems with most of
their equipment and facilities remaining idle.
</P>
<P>
The fair was sponsored by the Beijing Economic Development
Investment Company (BEDIC) and the Beijing Property Rights
Transaction Service Center (BPRTS).
</P>
<P>
BEDIC President Wang Qi said that transactions will mainly
involve negotiated transfers. Auctions will be introduced in cases
where there are more than one bidder.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that none of the city's over 34,000 industrial
enterprises had previously been sold, a situation quite different
from the rapid development of property rights transfers in
southern cities.
</P>
<P>
China has established over 190 intermediary agencies dealing
with property rights transfers.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai witnessed some 300 property rights transfers in the
first half of this year, with the total transaction volume of 5.3
billion yuan representing a five-fold rise on the previous year's
period.
</P>
<P>
China is proceeding in line with the economic development
policy adopted by the 15th National Congress of the Communist
Party of China and is urging small- to medium-sized enterprises to
seek development by reorganizing assets and introducing various
modes of ownership.
</P>
<P>
The policy stipulates that collectives, individuals and foreign
investors are permitted to purchase the assets and management
rights of state-owned enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
