<DOCNO> XIE19971115.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas-Funded Businesses Benefit East Chinese City's Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Overseas-funded businesses
have become a big force in the economic growth of Suzhou in east
China's Jiangsu province.
</P>
<P>
The city set up its first foreign-funded enterprise in 1984. To
date, 40 percent of the local companies are backed by overseas
investment. Foreign-funded enterprises had 2.4 billion US dollars
worth of exports in 1996, accounting for 62 percent of the local
total.
</P>
<P>
The city now has 39 foreign-funded enterprises each with
exports of more than 10 million US dollars annually.
</P>
<P>
During the first half of this year, overseas-funded enterprises
paid 469 million yuan in added-value and consumer goods taxes and
121 million yuan in income and business taxes, accounting for
nearly 17 percent of local revenues.
</P>
<P>
Of the world's 500 top multinationals, 56 have funded projects
in Suzhou in machinery, electronics, iron and steel, chemicals,
and pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
This year the city has begun with 56 new projects, 28 of which
have introduced overseas investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
