<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos Calls for Strict Compliance of Ceasefire Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos today called for strict compliance by both the government
and the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) with the ground rules
of a general ceasefire forged between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Both sides should refrain from all acts that might set back
efforts to "establish permanent peace in Mindanao," the southern
Philippines, Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
The government and the MILF signed a general ceasefire
agreement in July this year. To make it effective, they discussed
the basic rules to implement it in their ensuing negotiations and
inked a ground-rule agreement on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ramos hailed the signing of the agreement, which eventually
paved the way for the holding of formal talks between the two
sides, as "a significant milestone in the peace process."
</P>
<P>
The agreement bans both sides from committing hostile acts such
as kidnappings, attacks, bombings, robberies, raids, ambuscades,
summary executions and other criminal atrocities.
</P>
<P>
It also identified the specific ground rules covering the
movement of both government and MILF forces, conduct of inquiry by
an independent ceasefire watch group, disposition of violations of
the ceasefire and security of the government and MILF negotiators.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ramos congratulated both negotiating panels for
their efforts in coming out with the rules.
</P>
<P>
"Indeed, their complementary efforts are clear manifestation
that we are one nation and one people who can work together toward
the attainment of a lasting peace and continuing economic
developing in Mindanao," he said.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is a 12,000-member group operating in Mindanao. After
the mainstream Moro National Liberation Front signed a full peace
deal with the government in September 1996, it became the largest
rebel group in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
