<DOCNO> XIE19971115.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF to Oppose Creation of Independent Asian Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Chief of the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) Michel Camdessus said here today that the IMF
would oppose the creation of an independent Asian fund to bail out
troubled regional economies from the currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference shortly after his arrival, he
said that whatever financial mechanism can be put in place, "it
should not compete... or reduce the strengthen of the IMF
qualities and conditionalities."
</P>
<P>
Camdessus' remarks came ahead of a meeting to be held here on
November 18-19 by deputy finance ministers from the United States,
Japan and Asian economies to discuss the details of the
multi-billion dollar fund.
</P>
<P>
The proposed Asian fund should complement IMF programs and that
any spending it makes to help countries should be linked to the
IMF, he said, adding that if not, such a fund would be questioned
by regional markets.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus is on a Southeast Asia tour which has brought him to
Malaysia, Indonesia, Singapore and Thailand to discuss the
financial situation in the region.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in the last leg of the tour, Camdessus is
expected to discuss with Philippine government officials the
country's economic situation and its proposed exit from the IMF.
</P>
<P>
Saying that the country was less affected by the regional
currency turmoil due to sound economic fundamentals, he urged the
Philippine government to further strengthen its financial sector.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
