<DOCNO> XIE19971115.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Province Records Rapid Electronics Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, November 15 (Xinhua) -- The electronics industry in
southern China's Guangdong Province increased its output to 71.1
billion yuan in the first 10 months of 1997, up 38 percent from
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Electronics has been the fastest growing sector in Guangdong
during the past few years at an average annual growth rate of 35
percent, a provincial government official said.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 local color TV brands exceed other provinces in
output. Guangdong's output of magnetic heads used in computers
makes up one-third of the world's total, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Among the 55 most popular electronics appliances in China, 24
came from Guangdong.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong has 40-odd electronics firms directly under the
Ministry of Electronics Industry with a combined fixed assets of
12.3 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
They generated an output value of 61.5 billion yuan in 1996,
accounting for one-fifth of the national total.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971115.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers of East China Province Enjoy Rising Purchasing Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Rural residents in Fujian, a
coastal province in east China, purchased goods valued at 22.3
billion yuan during the first nine months of this year, up 16.8
percent on the same 1996 period.
</P>
<P>
The increase was attributed to the fact that the per capita
income of farmers jumped by 9.6 percent to 2,037 yuan during the
first three quarters of the year.
</P>
<P>
Experts noted the rural areas in Fujian offer great potential
for the consumer goods market, while urban areas in the province
currently face saturation. Fujian's 25.95 million rural residents
account for 81 percent of its total population.
</P>
<P>
Statistics for 1996 show that every 100 urban households owned
79 refrigerators and 92 washing machines, with the figure for
rural areas standing at nine refrigerators and 21 washing
machines respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971115.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Official in Charge of Oil-for-Food Arrives in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Chief of the U.N. commission
for monitoring the oil-for-food deal between the U.N. and Iraq
Benitton Stefan arrived here Friday on a week-long mission, a
U.N. source said today.
</P>
<P>
Stefan is scheduled to hold a series of meetings with Iraqi
leaders before heading for the northern provinces on a four-day
visit. He will leave Iraq on November 23.
</P>
<P>
The main aim of Stefan's visit is to get acquainted with the
humanitarian situation in Iraq, the source added.
</P>
<P>
This is Stefan's first visit to Iraq since he was appointed
head of the commission by U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan in
October.
</P>
<P>
The current tension between Iraq and the United Nations over
the U.N. weapons inspectors did not affect the operation of the
oil-for-food program, according to the monitors of the deal.
</P>
<P>
Stefan's visit came when Iraq was facing possible U.S. military
strike due to its non-cooperation with the U.N. weapons
inspection teams and its expulsion of Americans working for the
U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of dismantling Iraqi
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
This showed the determination of the international
organization to go on with the implementation of the
oil-for-food deal and the supply of foodstuffs to the Iraqi
people who are suffering under the seven-year-old U.N. sanctions
imposed after Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food deal which was launched last December,
Iraq was allowed to export 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil
over six months to buy food, medicine and other humanitarian
goods for its people.
</P>
<P>
The crippling economic sanctions cannot be lifted unless
U.N. arms inspectors verify that Iraq has eliminated all its
weapons of mass destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
