<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Management of Accumulated Public Housing Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Regulations on accumulated
public housing funds drafted by the Standing Committee of the
Guangzhou City People's Congress have been approved by the Standing
Committee of the Guangdong Provincial People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
The regulations will go into effect on January 1, 1998,
according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou, the capital of south China's Guangdong Province, is
working diligently to raise its per capita living space to 12
sq.m. by the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
"Implementation of the regulations will provide legal guarantees
for realizing the goal, and will also promote housing
construction," according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou was one of a number of Chinese cities designated to
introduce pilot housing reform. The city introduced accumulated
public funds for housing on April 1, 1992. Over 1.02 million
employees working for 7,000-odd enterprises and institutions had
contributed 1.72 billion yuan to the special fund by the end of
September this year.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou's current per capita living space stands at 10 sq.m.,
up dramatically on the three sq.m. level in 1980. More than
20,000 poor families with living space of less than five sq.m. will
move into new housing by the end of this year, according to
officials.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
