<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Auto-Maker Aiming High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 15 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai Automobile
Industry Company (SAIC) has embarked on an ambitious plan to raise
over two billion yuan on the Shanghai Stock Exchange and use the money
to turn itself into the largest auto-maker in China.
</P>
<P>
The company expects to increase its sales value to 100 billion
yuan and its annual output to 400,000 cars by 2000. Its
total sales were only 41.2 billion yuan last year.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the funds raised will be invested in the
Shanghai General Motor Co., Ltd. (SGM) to develop a luxury
Buick-brand car, with the rest going toward the purchase of three
automobile industrial companies, according to SAIC officials.
</P>
<P>
SAIC holds half of the shares of SGM, a joint venture with the
U.S.-based General Motors Co. that involves a total investment of
three billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
GSM's annual sales are expected to reach 11.5 billion yuan by
the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Volkswagen Co, Ltd, another joint venture of SAIC
with German-based Volkswagen, will produce 230,000 cars, with a
total sale of 35 billion yuan, this year.
</P>
<P>
SAIC will also complete building of a technological research
center within three years to design new parts and equipment for
its cars.
</P>
<P>
SAIC will control nearly 40 percent of the total shares of
China's automobile market by the year 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
