<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Ruling Party Secretariat Gets New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Philip Mangula has
retained his post as the secretary-general of the newly
constituted National Executive Committee (NEC) of Tanzania's
ruling party, while the two deputy chiefs have been replaced.
</P>
<P>
The NEC session under the ruling Chama Cha Mapinduzi (CCM)
national chairman, President Benjamin Mkapa, appointed Friday
Hassan Mussa Takrima as the new deputy Secretary General for
Zanzibar and Brigadier-General Hassan Ngwilizi, the Deputy
Secretary General for Mainland.
</P>
<P>
Takrima takes over the position from Ali Ameir Mohamed, the
Home Affairs Minister, while Brigadier General Ngwilizi replaces
Ukiwaona-Ditopile Mzuzuri, according to a statement issued by
CCM.
</P>
<P>
The statement said, Abdulsalaam Issa Khatibu, Deputy Minister
for Finance, takes over as National Planning Secretary while
Jackson Msome becomes the new CCM Publicity Secretary, a post
which was held by John Mgeja.
</P>
<P>
The NEC also elected Abdallah Kigoda, Minister for Energy and
Minerals, as new National CCM Treasurer, replacing Ms Sifa Swai.
</P>
<P>
The one-day NEC meeting also endorsed 11 CCM members proposed
by CCM National Chairman Mkapa, to become NEC members.
</P>
<P>
The country's constitution allows the chairman to propose a
list of 15 CCM members to sit in the NEC sessions with approval
from the NEC. The remaining four members would be elected in a
later date.
</P>
<P>
The NEC appointed veteran politician Rashidi Kawawa as
chairman of the CCM Board of Trustees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
