<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Upsets Olympic Champions Netherlands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OSAKA, Japan, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Asian Champion China
produced the biggest surprise Saturday at the men's competition of
the current world volleyball Grand Champions Cup, upseting Olympic
and European Champion the Netherlands 3-1 in a match played with
the newly introduced 25-minutes rule.
</P>
<P>
The highly spirited Chinese spikers clinched the contest over
their Dutch rivals 15-13, 15-10, 12-15 and 15-5.
</P>
<P>
Dutch head coach Toon Gerbrands claimed his team was the first
victim of the new 25-minute rule, which restricts the first four
sets of a match to be played under service-point scoring system
within 25-minutes.
</P>
<P>
If any of the first four sets goes more than 25-minutes, the
game will be changed to rally-point scoring system till a team
completes the necessary winning points of 15 or win the
tie-breaker by two points.
</P>
<P>
"First, I should say we played a very bad game today, but you
can see what happened with the time system, the weaker team can
win by luck." Gerbrands told a post-game press conference.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch side led 12-10 when the scoring board turned into
rally-points system and China tied it at 13-all with two smart
smashes and one lucky drop. Then blocker Zheng Liang sealed the
set for China by knocking down two powerfull smashes from Ducth
top spiker Bas Van De Goor in the last two plays.
</P>
<P>
"We led 12-10 in the first set, and suddenly the system
changed, the weaker team tied the scores by lucks. Otherwise we
would win the set." said Gerbrands.
</P>
<P>
"With the new system, we had no chance to rally. That's very
difficult. Our problems began after that (losing the first set)"
he added.
</P>
<P>
But Chinese Coach Wang Jiawei, who guided his boys for their
first Asian Championship title in 18-year last October, had
different opinions about the new time rule: "The team with less
mistakes could win matches with the new rule."
</P>
<P>
"We know they are the Olympic Champion and European
champion. To play against such a strong team, we had nothing to
lose. We want to learn in physical and mental aspects from them.
But in the first set, I found they didn't show their best forms.
So I am confident that even if the match were played in old
system, we still would have chance to beat them today, " he said.
</P>
<P>
In the second set, China led 13-10 into the rally-point
overtime. With fast breaking and solid blocking on the net, they
left no gap for their Dutch rivals to steal the game.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Saturday, hosts Japan beat Australia in straight
sets 3-0. The Japanese team controlled everything on the court
and never looked back before routing their younger Australian
counterparts 15-4, 15-10 and 15-3 with various weapons of
smashing, droping and blocks.
</P>
<P>
The Australian team, picked up by the International Volleyball
Association (FIVA) to replace African champion, would learn a lot
from its counterparts, which include continental champions of the
Netherlands, Cuba, Brazil and China. Japan took part in the event
as hosts.
</P>
<P>
"We has great disadvantage today. Our four key players arrived
in Japan last night and had no practice. This event is a
fantastic learning oppotunity for us." said Stelio De Rocco, the
head of Australia.
</P>
<P>
In Friday's last contest, Northern American Brazil rallied from
the first-set down to beat the Northern, Central American champion
Cuba 13-15, 15-10, 15-4 and 15-9.
</P>
<P>
The 12-day tournament started on Friday with the women's
competition, which include continental champions of Cuba, Brazil,
Russia and China, as well as FIVA selected team South Korea and
hosts Japan. The men's and women's events are played in alternate
days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
