<HEADLINE> U.S. Secretary of State Visits Pakistan Sunday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 15 (Xinhua) -- The US Secretary of State,
Madeleine Albright, will make a two-day official visit to Pakistan
starting from November 16, a Foreign Office spokesman announced
today.
</P>
<P>
"The visit of the U.S. Secretary of State is expected to
contribute significantly towards establishing a new partnership
between the two countries for peace, progress and prosperity," the
spokesman said at a weekly news conference here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
During her stay in Pakistan, Albright will have talks with
Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan on the entire range of bilateral
matters as well as regional and global issues of mutual interest,
particularly Kashmir and Afghanistan, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
She will also call on President Farooq Leghari and Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif, he added.
</P>
<P>
The visit, which is the first by a U.S. Secretary of State to
South Asia since 1983, is in line with the renewed U.S. focus on
the region, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Assistant Secretary Karl Inderfurth and Under Secretary of
State Thomas Pickering visited Pakistan in September and October
respectively, he said, adding these high level visits will lead to
that of President Bill Clinton in the first quarter of next year.
 
</P>
