<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coastal, Border Regions of China Enjoy Foreign Trade Boom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 15 (Xinhua) -- China's coastal and border
regions, excluding the Inner Mongolia and Tibet autonomous
regions, recored a foreign trade volume of 180 billion US dollars
for the first nine months of this year, up 18 percent on the 1996
period.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong Province ranked first with a foreign trade volume of
52 billion US dollars in the period. Shanghai ranked second at
17.6 billion US dollars and Jiangsu province held third place with
16.9 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen of 14 provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities
registered rising export volumes, with Yunnan Province being the
only region failing to do so. The Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region
registered a 42 percent increase in exports, with Guangdong
recording a 26 percent rise and Fujian a 22 percent
increase.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning Province, Jiangsu Province and Tianjin Municipality
recorded a 56-percent, 32 percent and 24 percent increase in
imports, respectively. Hainan's import volume fell by 44 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
