<DOCNO> XIE19971115.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet's First International-Aided Agricultural Project Completed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, November 15 (Xinhua) -- The Tibet Autonomous Region's
first agricultural development project assisted by an
international organization has been completed after eight years.
</P>
<P>
The project, aided by the World Food Program of the United
Nations and covering more than 6,600 hectares of land in the Lhasa
River Valley, has greatly improved local agricultural and stock
raising conditions, according to the local agricultural department.
</P>
<P>
"It has settled the region's irrigation problem through the
construction of water conservation works," said a local
agricultural official, adding that more than 2,600 hectares of
farmland has been added to the irrigation area.
</P>
<P>
As a result, a net increase of some 700 tons of grain will be
added to the annual output of the area covered by the project.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the project has helped the region raise the
husbandry output through grass cultivation and feed
improvement. The daily milk output per cow will increase by 1.13
kg, and the number of sheep grazing on every hectares of grassland
will exceed 45.
</P>
<P>
The project, launched in 1990 and with an overall investment of
nearly 100 million yuan (about 12.5 million US dollars), has
planted 2,000-plus hectares of trees, cultivated nearly 600
hectares of grass, added a length of 580 km to the region's
ditches, and provided training for 36,000 people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
