<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Imposes Yellow Fever Vaccination Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Travelers from yellow
fever endemic countries will need a vaccination certificate
recognized by the World Health Organization (WHO) to enter
Malaysia, its Health Minister Chua JUI Meng said today.
</P>
<P>
The entry condition imposed with immediate effect also applied
to Malaysian travelers who visited these countries, 33 in Africa
and 10 in South America, he told a news conference here today.
</P>
<P>
The countries on the African continent include Angola, Burkina
Faso, Chad, Ethiopia, Ghana, Gambia, Kenya, Liberia, Senegal,
Somalia and Zambia while those in South America are Bolivia,
Brazil, Colombia, Ecuador, French-Guyana, Guyana, Panama, Peru,
Surinam and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
He said those without the vaccination certificate would undergo
quarantining process for a maximum of six days, which is the
incubation period of the disease, at entry points.
</P>
<P>
"This is to protect our citizens because our population is not
used to the infection of the virus," he said, adding that although
the country has yellow fever virus vector, the population is free
of the disease so far.
</P>
<P>
Yellow fever is an acute, infectious tropical disease caused by
a virus transmitted through the bite of yellow-fever mosquito.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the vaccination certificate is valid for 10
years and travelers to endemic countries must be vaccinated 10
days before departure. There are seven vaccination centers in the
country for Malaysian travelers.
</P>
<P>
He said the Foreign Ministry had also been directed by the
Cabinet to notify Malaysian embassies and high commissions
overseas in the affected countries on the ruling.
</P>
<P>
He said his government was serious over the ruling in view of
the expanding close ties in trade and investment as well as in
education between Malaysia and countries concerned due to its
active South-South cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that if an epidemic were to occur in a
population like Malaysia, the death rate from the disease could be
up to 50 per cent for adults and up to 75 per cent for children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971115.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
