<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia, Europe Urged to Take Measures to Promote Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Asian and European countries
are urged to take measures to promote their cooperation in tourism
as the industry plays an important role in their economic and
trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
First of all, visa processing procedures should be simplified,
said Asian and European representatives in a chairman's statement
released here on Friday after the second Asia-Europe business
forum (AEBF ii) closed.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, improvement should be made in the issuance of
multiple visas, extension of validity, and renewal of visa, said
the representatives from 10 Asian nations and 15 European nations
who attended the two-day event.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, consumer protection directives and guidelines in both
regions should be made transparent to reduce the impact of these
rules on travelers and increase tourism.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, Asia and Europe should enhance their cooperation in
professional training and education in tourism to meet the
challenges of globalization as professionalism and quality
services will play a growing important role in the future.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the representatives also recommended that the
governments should simplify custom formalities and regulations for
international conferences and exhibitions and liberalize the
services to promote tourism.
</P>
<P>
Rules on imports of printed materials, brochures, and samples
used for international conferences and exhibitions should be eased
and exempted from import duties.
</P>
<P>
Refundable bank guarantee system should be established for
re-export of equipment used for exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
In connection with liberalization process, the representatives
said that tourism activities should be managed under freer
competition.
</P>
<P>
Existing restrictions such as the issuance of tour guide
licenses and work permits should be liberalized in both Asia and
Europe.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
