<HEADLINE> Police Take in 55 People for Questioning in Colombo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, November 15 (Xinhua) -- At least 55 people have been
taken in for questioning in Colombo following Friday's power plant
bombing by the Tamil rebels, police said here today.
</P>
<P>
A number of the detained have been released after being cleared
of any connection with the incident, which was blamed on the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE), police said. Among those
questioned were 11 women.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a tight security network is in force in Colombo and
its suburbs.
</P>
<P>
Police also concluded after having done initial investigations
that the LTTE is lacking of "bomb experts." They said the rebels
who sneaked into the power plant apparently did a hurried job.
</P>
<P>
Six out of nine magnetic explosive devices they planted on four
oil tanks were duds, according to police. Early reports said there
were a total of ten explosive devices.
</P>
<P>
The biggest thermal power plant of Sri Lanka caught fire Friday
morning at around 5 o'clock due to the explosions of the devices.
Fire brigade and security personnel brought the fire under control
within about half an hour.
</P>
<P>
No one was killed or wounded in the incident and the plant
sustained minor damage.  
</P>
