<HEADLINE> Zambia Denies Arms Supply to UNITA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 15 (Xinhua) -- A senior Zambian official has
denied reports that the Zambian government has been supplying
arms by air to Angola's former rebel movement UNITA, Times of
Zambia reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted state house Cabinet Minister Eric Silwamba as
saying Friday that the Zambian government has never been involved
in the supply of arms to UNITA but that some private companies
have been violating Zambia's airspace to engage in the illegal
arms deal.
</P>
<P>
Reports of Zambian government's involvement are totally false
and the issue is now as good as resolved, Silwamba said.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a meeting with visiting Angolan Home
Affairs Minister Santana Andre Pitra.
</P>
<P>
The latest issue of Star of South Africa, according to Times
of Zambia, quoted diplomatic sources in Luanda, Angola as warning
Zambia to cut off UNITA's supplies from its western region or
face the same sort of military intervention that toppled the
governments in the two Congos, which were both supplying UNITA
with weapons.
</P>
<P>
Silwamba noted that a South African company named Metex
International which is involved in the arms deal with UNITA has
been banned and its personnel deported from Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Some senior Zambian personnel at Ndola Airport who were linked
to the deal has been sacked and the cabinet has signed a
statutory instrument empowering the Zambia Air Force to shoot any
plane using the country's airspace without permission, said the
minister.
</P>
<P>
"We can only confirm that our airspace was violated at one
time and we took remedial measures. Our Angolan friends were
right to complain. But relations are now very good," said
Silwamba.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the Angolan minister said reports of
Angola's accusing Zambia of being involved in the arms deal with
UNITA are merely trying to strain relations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
However, he complained that some countries are still
supporting UNITA despite a United Nations arms sanctions.
However, he added, the issue is now being resolved by various
committees of the Southern African Development Community.
</P>
</TEXT>
