<HEADLINE> UN Worried Over UNITA Disbanding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, November 15 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations observers
in Angola have expressed worries that the National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) has not approved them of
restarting the disbanding of UNITA militiamen based in Bailundo.
</P>
<P>
The Angola News Agency today quoted Nicholas Duse, head of
U.N. observers in central Angola as saying that the work should
have started on November 10, but no approval has been given by
UNITA leadership so far.
</P>
<P>
Registration of UNITA militiamen headquartered in Bailundo was
unilaterally halted by the former rebel movement on October 30
when the U.N Security Council announced sanctions on the
movement.
</P>
<P>
So far, according to Duse, the number of UNITA generals and
other senior officers and soldiers in Bailundo is not available
to the U.N. observers. Up to October 30, only 80 UNITA militiamen
had registered and handed over their weapons to the observers.
</P>
<P>
People should wait patiently for the change of UNITA, since
without peace, Angola would have no other way out, Duse noted.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the meeting between Angolan President Eduardo
dos Santos and UNITA Chairman Jonas Savimbi at the end of this
month will generate new stimulus to the peace process in Angola.
</P>
</TEXT>
