<DOCNO> XIE19971115.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3.5 Million Kenyans Might Carry Hepatitis B </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 15 (Xinhua) -- About 3.5 million Kenyans
could be carriers of hepatitis "B", which is the major cause of
liver cancer and liver cirrhosis, according to a specialist at
the Kenya Medical Research Institute (KEMRI).
</P>
<P>
Ten percent of all adult male in this eastern African country
have hepatitis "B", Doctor Fredrick Okoth was quoted by today's
Kenya Times newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
"In Kenya, hepatitis 'B' is causing as much mortality as AIDS.
It is just that hepatitis 'B' is not highlighted as AIDS is," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The disease is more prevalent in north-western Kenya,
particularly in Pokot and Turkana where the prevalence rate hits
a 30 percent mark, the doctor noted.
</P>
<P>
Hepatitis "B", a progressive disease transmitted through
exchange of a variety of bodily fluids, is responsible for 80
percent of all liver cancers.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization estimates that the disease
infects almost 50 million more people annually and kills about
two million every year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971115.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia, Europe Urged to Boost Cooperation in Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Asian and European
representatives Friday called for a stronger cooperation between
Asia and Europe in the field of investment.
</P>
<P>
"Investment is an important and inseparable part of the overall
economic relationship between Asia and Europe," the
representatives said in a chairman's statement released at the end
of the Second Asia-Europe Business Forum (AEBF ii) here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation in developing the financial services sector in Asia
is a vital element in attracting more European investment, said
the representatives participating the two-day event.
</P>
<P>
Recent turbulence in Asia's financial markets only reinforces
the need to find ways to encourage and increase investment in the
area, they noted.
</P>
<P>
The availability of both local currency and foreign exchange
long-term finance was identified as a crucial element in
stimulating and supporting investment, particularly in
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
this will require the development of debt markets in Asian
countries and an enhanced role for multilateral financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
Asia and Europe should also strengthen their technical
cooperation to assist national financial and banking systems to
improve the climate for investment.
</P>
<P>
The technical cooperation should cover assistance in creating
more sophisticated financial markets with particular attention to
developing domestic capital, bond and stock exchange markets.
</P>
<P>
Such assistance should extend to training and human resources
development.
</P>
<P>
The representatives from 10 Asian nations and 15 European
nations pointed out that further deregulation and liberalization
of Asia's financial markets have a vital role in restoring the
confidence of foreign investors in Asia.
</P>
<P>
They strongly supported an early and successful conclusion to
the World Trade Organization negotiations on financial services.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the representatives stressed the importance of the
stability of financial markets, proposing that international
financial institutions should maintain their observation of
international capital flows with an aim to give early warning of
potential problems and avoid any possible market disruption.
</P>
<P>
They expressed hopes that Asian and European banks to forge a
closer link in exchange of information.
</P>
<P>
On finance to investment, the forum saw a pressing need to make
improvement in this respect and attached particular importance to
improving access for small and medium-sized enterprises to venture
capital funds.
</P>
<P>
It recommended governments to consider other means to back
investment such as guarantees and insurance.
</P>
<P>
Also, the representatives urged Asia-Europe Meeting (ASEM)
countries to make full use of the Asia-Europe investment promote
action plan, which was put forward by the AEBF i held in Paris
last year and is due to be endorsed at the second ASEM scheduled
for April 3-4 next year in London.
</P>
<P>
"The investment experts group (IEG) could act as a valuable
forum for coordination of efforts in this sphere," they said.
</P>
<P>
The representatives urged Asian and European governments to
establish investment regimes offering mutually beneficial
conditions, while taking account of their diverse economic
situations.
</P>
<P>
These regimes could draw upon the work in hand in several
international bodies on investment protection principles, they
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
