<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Product Standards Harmonized in E. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Forty-two standards of
products have been harmonized and another 62 are in the process
of being harmonized within the East African Cooperation which is
composed of Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by the Managing Director of Kenya Bureau of
Standards (KBS) Philip Okundi on Friday who also said that the
three east African countries had signed an agreement aimed at
harmonizing the standards of their products, the Kenya Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, goods bearing the standardization marks
from their National Standards Bureau would be accepted without
further testing or inspection.
</P>
<P>
Okundi said the KBS had launched the "Diamond Mark of Quality"
to facilitate Kenyan manufacturers to promote their products in
this east African region.
</P>
<P>
Since its launch, he noted, the standardization mark has
increasingly earned respect as a symbol of product quality both
locally and in Tanzania and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Okundi official presented the "Diamond Mark of
Quality" permits to Unga Limited which is the first miller
presented with the permits in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that following the presentation, the products
of the Unga Group of Companies can easily be traded in the three
east African countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
