<HEADLINE> Boeing Resumes 747 Jet Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, November 14 (Xinhua) -- Boeing Corp has resumed
production on its 747 jumbo jet assembly line, though efforts to
solve production problems are not complete.
</P>
<P>
Boeing's announcement today ended a 20-day shutdown during
which the production of 747-400's was halted and that of 737's was
slowed at a cost of 2.6 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The shutdown was ordered to eliminate problems caused by trying
to meet booming demand for airlines around the world.
</P>
<P>
Boeing, the world's largest aerospace manufacturer
headuqartered in Seattle, Washington State, received a record of
712 orders for new planes last year, up from 338 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The company now will resume turning out four 747s a month, and
is expected to increase its capacity to five a month by mid-1998,
said Brian Ames, spokesman for Boeing.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Boeing said the shutdown would result in the
postponed delivery of at least a dozen aircraft. 
</P>
</TEXT>
