<HEADLINE> PNA Decides to Boycott Doha Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 15 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) has officially decided to boycott the Middle
East and North Africa economic conference due to open Sunday in
Qatar to protest Israel's derailment of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The decision to boycott the regional economic conference to be
held in Qatari capital Doha was made at a three-hour PNA Cabinet
meeting held in the West Bank city of Ramallah Friday night.
</P>
<P>
Hanan Ashrawi, Minister of Higher Education, told reporters
after the cabinet meeting that the PNA decided to boycott the
Doha conference in order to protest Israel's refusal to honor
the signed peace accords.
</P>
<P>
Ashrawi condemned what she called "Israel's deliberate attempt
of derailing the peace process, refusing to implement the signed
agreements and continuing settlement activities."
</P>
<P>
The PNA's decision to boycott the Doha conference cast further
shadow over the annual economic gathering which was originally
initiated in 1994 to consolidate the peace process through
promoting Israeli-Arab economic cooperation and development.
</P>
<P>
Adding to the traditional list of boycotters which include
Syria, Lebanon, Iran and Iraq, this year leading Arab countries
such as Egypt, Saudi Arabia, Morocco, Bahrain, and the United Arab
Emirates have also decided to shy away from the conference to
express their anger at the stalemate in the peace process caused
by Israeli hardline policies. But Jordan, Kuwait, Yemen, Tunisia
and Oman will attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy announced Thursday that he
would not attend the Doha conference and the Israeli delegation
will be headed by Industry and Trade Minister Natan Sharansky.
</P>
<P>
Levy's announcement was issued despite the fact that United
States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who herself is to
participate in the meeting, had been trying to press Israel to
send Levy.
</P>
<P>
The massive boycott of Doha conference highlights the
increasing isolation of Israel and unity of Arab countries at a
time when the Middle East peace process is virtually deadlocked
on all tracks because of Israel's hardline policies and its
refusal to implement the signed agreements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
