<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysia's CPO, Tin, Rubber Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's markets of
crude palm oil (CPO) physicals, tin and rubber closed the week
mixed.
</P>
<P>
This week, the CPO physicals market was firm, supported by
buying interest for the Malaysian palm oil from private Pakistani
and Indian traders and by the talks that Indonesia may impose
quota for its crude palm oil exports.
</P>
<P>
Ivan Wong, a private crop forecaster, released his estimate on
Friday that Malaysia's October palm oil output at 922,000 tons,
less one percent from September's output.
</P>
<P>
Wong put end-October stocks at 1.005 million tons against the
Palm Oil Registration and Licensing Authority's figure at 877,704
tons for the end of September, 1997.
</P>
<P>
November South closed the week 65 ringgit (19.69 U.S. dollars)
higher to 1,710 ringgit (518.18 U.S. dollars) per ton.
</P>
<P>
The CPO physicals are expected to extend its uptrend next week
on the anticipated continuous strong buying interest, a dealer
said.
</P>
<P>
On the Kuala Lumpur Tin Market (KLTM), tin started on the
higher note this week at 18.19 ringgit (5.51 U.S. dollars) per kg
as the three-month tin on the London Metal Exchange (LME)
rebounded by 80 U.S. dollars per ton last Friday but the earlier
gains were eroded on Thursday after tin price on the LME dipped by
80 U.S. dollars per ton overnight.
</P>
<P>
However, strong buying interests on Friday ahead of the weekend
aided by the softening of the ringgit, pulled the tin price from
17.95 ringgit per kg back to 18 ringgit level.
</P>
<P>
Tin closed the week at 18.01 ringgit (5.45 U.S. dollars) per
kg, up 19 sen from last week's close at 17.82 ringgit (5.4 U.S.
dollars) per kg.
</P>
<P>
Accumulated turnover this week totaled 358 tons against 415
tons last week.
</P>
<P>
On the Malaysian rubber market, December RSS One closed the
week 10 sen lower to 277.00 sen (83.93 U.S. cents) per kg while
SMR 20 slipped by 8.5 sen to 277.50 sen (84 U.S. cents) per kg.
</P>
<P>
The International Natural Rubber Organization (INRO) daily
market indicator for November 13 was at 202.40 Malaysia/Singapore
cents per kg against 207.31 cents on November 6.
</P>
<P>
The five-day moving average stood at 204.86 cents per kg this
week against 208.12 cents per kg last week.
</P>
<P>
The local rubber market is expected to experience slow and
quiet trading next week as most players are likely to take to the
sidelines in the absence of fresh leads amid poor market sentiment
which is not only prevailing in Malaysia but also in the region
following the economic instability in Thailand as well as the
regional currencies, a dealer said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
