<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Kuala Lumpur Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 15 (Xinhua) -- The Kuala Lumpur Stock
Exchange (KLSE) ended the week sharply lower on lack of buying
support amid concerns of high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The 100-quality stocks Composite Index fell 29.98 points to
677.47, the all-share Emas Index dropped 9.99 points to 189.67,
the Second Board Index lost 19.45 points to 328.17 while the
Industrial Index was down 105.07 points at 1,326.11.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark touched an intra-week high of 700.96 on Monday
and a low of 671.86 on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The market started the week broadly easier in reaction to
heavyweight utility, Tenaga Nasional's much lower profit of 144.7
million ringgit (43.85 million U.S. dollars) following a loss of
1.3 billion ringgit (393.94 million U.S. dollars) in foreign
exchange.
</P>
<P>
On the local front, players remained jittery over the banking
sector despite assurance by International Monetary Fund managing
director Michel Camdessus that Malaysia's banking sector did not
face serious problems.
</P>
<P>
They were bearish over the regional outlook and worried over
the possibility of rising rates after banks raised their base
lending rates to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
The KLSE showed an initial reaction to rally on Wall Street
which rallied on Alan Greenspan's testimony to the Congress that
the impact of the currency turmoil in Asia on the U.S. economy was
modest before rises were capped by concerns.
</P>
<P>
On the KLSE, the mainboard volume totaled 760.462 million
shares worth 2.574 billion ringgit (780 million U.S. dollars) from
1.250 billion shares valued at 4.993 billion ringgit (1.51 billion
U.S. dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
The second board turnover was 152.31 million shares worth
957.97 million ringgit (290.29 million U.S. dollars) from 190.259
million shares valued at 1.41 billion ringgit (426.67 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Off-market deals narrowed to 167.06 million shares worth 1.16
billion ringgit (350 million U.S. dollars) from 129.09 million
shares valued at 1.19 billion ringgit (about 361.21 million U.S.
dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
Ink maker Toyochem Corporation made its debut on the second
board on Tuesday by posting a premium 30 sen over its offer price
of 3.10 ringgit before ending the day with a 12 sen discount and
finishing the week at 2.49 ringgit.
</P>
<P>
Six counters -- Unza, Berjaya Capital, Berjaya Singer, Hwa Tai,
Denko Industrial and Repco -- requested for suspension of trading
of their shares this week.
</P>
<P>
The 10 most active counters were MP Land at 3.80 ringgit, down
18 sen; Renong flat at 3.00 ringgit; Sunrise, down 50 sen to 3.60
ringgit; Eden down 38 sen to 4.16 ringgit; United Engineers, up 10
sen to 6.20 ringgit; Sime Darby down 14 sen to 4.36 ringgit;
Commerce up three sen to 2.63 ringgit; Selangor Dredging down a
sen to 90 sen; Mancon down six sen to 3.58 ringgit and Arus Murni
down 19 sen to 2.32 ringgit.
</P>
<P>
Consumer products accounted for 35.536 million shares traded,
industrial products 64.606 million shares, construction 110.138
million shares, trading/service 144.393 million shares, IPC 6.563
million shares, finance 94.002 million shares, hotels 18.286
million shares, properties 196.659 million shares, plantation
21.069 million shares, mining 5.121 million shares, trusts 754,000
shares, closed fund 550,000 shares and loans 20.525 million
shares. 
</P>
