<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minister Discloses Gender Imbalances in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Minister of Gender
and Community Development Janat Mukwaya said here that
decision-making is still predominantly a male domain in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
She was quoted by local paper The New Vision as saying Friday
that at ministerial level, six out of 54 ministers are women,
which was a percentage of 11.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Gender imbalances are equally evident in the civil service,
health and education sectors, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
"In the civil service, women make up only 19.4 percent of the
total permanent secretaries, while out of 45 chief administrative
officers, five are women," she noted.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, although women constitute 70 to 80 percent of the
agricultural labor force, only 7 percent own land and 30 percent
have access to land and control over proceeds.
</P>
<P>
"Women's productivity is further hampered by inadequate access
to credit and general lack of skills and appropriate flow of and
access to information," Mukwaya added.
</P>
<P>
In the education sector, she said, gender imbalances are
evident in the literacy rate and access to education.
</P>
<P>
Quoting the 1991 population and housing census, Mukwaya said
61.3 percent of females are illiterate compared to 38.7 percent
males.
</P>
<P>
She disclosed gender imbalances while launching a national
gender policy as a legal framework which will guide policy makers
and all actors in development to redress existing gender
imbalances. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
