<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: LTTE Bombs Colombo to Divert Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, November 15 (Xinhua) -- The Liberation Tiger of Tamil
Eelam (LTTE) rebels once again proved they are Sri Lanka's biggest
obstacle on the hard road to peace when they planted bombs in a
power station in Colombo Friday morning, causing minor damages to
four oil tanks.
</P>
<P>
The incident was the second in one month by the LTTE following
the fatal bombing attack in the downtown business area of Colombo
on October 15, which killed 18 people and injured 100 more others.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts here said the two incidents showed that military
victory of the government troops in the north has forced the
rebels to resort to a new round of terrorist bombing attacks in
the capital to shake off their military pressure on battle fields.
</P>
<P>
Since the Operation Jayasikuru (Certain Victory) was launched
on May 13 to obtain a 70-kilometer-long transport line running to
the north, the troops have killed over 2,500 rebels.
</P>
<P>
The road is of vital strategic importance to the government,
which has to rely heavily on costly marine and airborne
transportation owing to constant rebel assaults on land route to
Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
The troops so far have cleared about two thirds of the road as
the operation entered its final phase. In desperation, the Tigers
slipped into Colombo seeking every chance to create chaos, the
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Unconfirmed reports said the rebel leader, Velupillai
Prabhakaran, had fled Sri Lanka for another country weeks ago. If
the reports were true, they could be further indicators that the
LTTE is facing an unfavorable situation in the north as a result
of offensives by the Army.
</P>
<P>
Foreign diplomatic sources here said due to the military
assaults in the north, several LTTE guerrilla troops had been
dispersed into small units after they lost contact with their
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Some of the units moved southwards and infiltrated into the
capital.
</P>
<P>
The diplomats said the bomb blast in Colombo last month was
carried out by one of such units. Those rebels had brought a total
of six truck-bombs into the city, according to the diplomats.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the Tigers defied tight security in Colombo and
attempted to give a bitter bite to the government when they
sneaked into Sri Lanka's biggest thermal power plant in pre-dawn
darkness and planted ten magnetic explosive devices on four oil
tanks.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the swift action of the security forces a fire
following the explosions of the devices was put off within 30
minutes, averting a major disaster.
</P>
<P>
A prominent feature of the two attacks was that the rebels
chose the traditional Full Moon Day to carry out their actions.
Both October 15 and November 14 were Full Moon Days when people do
not need to go to office.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
