<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Commercial Banks Take Action Against Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's commercial banks,
heavily burdened with non-performing loans, have started applying
the Bankruptcy Act, 1997 against defaulters to recover bad debts,
sources from the financial circles said today.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that till June 30 this year,
classified loans in this South Asian country stood at 122.383
billion taka (2.73 billion U.S. dollars) in 32 local, foreign and
nationalized commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
The Bankruptcy Act, 1997 was passed in Parliament this year to
expedite the recovery drive against defaulters in the backdrop of
huge burden on the banks because of non-refunding of loans by a
section of borrowers, the sources stated.
</P>
<P>
The state-owned Janata Bank recently reviewed the overall
situation regarding cases against loan defaulters and decided to
file cases against them under the Bankruptcy Act.
</P>
<P>
As the first step in filing cases under the newly enacted law,
the sources said, the Janata Bank Board asked the concerned
branches to inform the head office about progress in recovering
bad loans.
</P>
<P>
Besides, all the branches across the country have been
instructed to issue a 90-day notice to sue the defaulters,
according to the sources.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
