<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Census on Non-Beijing Permanent Residents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 15 (Xinhua) -- "I am a population surveyer in
this area and entrusted by the government, I have come to your
home to register non-Beijing permanent residents. I need your
help, and please answer a few questions."
</P>
<P>
Old lady Lu Xiulan, who works at the Dahongmen Neighborhood
Committee, feels uneasy when she introduces herself this way to
her "neighbors", a group of young non-Beijing residents. These
young people used to call her "aunt".
</P>
<P>
However, such introduction must be strictly used for surveyers
to carry out the first census on the migrant population in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Lu Xiulan and many other surveyers all underwent a week special
training before they started registration routines.
</P>
<P>
The total number of surveyers stands at over 60,000, consisting
of staffers of government departments, workers, farmers, students,
soldiers and retired elders.
</P>
<P>
Surveyers were trained to introduce the aim and significance of
the census, and they must be polite to those surveyed. Surveyers
must use standard language and can not ask misleading questions.
</P>
<P>
Lu Xiulan said, "I feel like a lawyer in a foreign film, not to
ask questions to mis-guide the surveyed."
</P>
<P>
Each surveyer carries a form specially-designed on the basis of
demography and statistics.
</P>
<P>
Based on experiences of past censuses, the Beijing Municipal
Statistics Bureau also works out a computer program for the
current census on non-Beijing residents, for future use in guiding
economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
The current census on the migrant population in Beijing started
on November 1 and will end today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
