<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuchma Seeks Donors for Chernobyl Tomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, November 14 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma
is to attend a donors meeting to collect more money for securing
the environmental safety of the sarcophagus covering the remains
of the destroyed Chernobyl reactor.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is scheduled to be held on November 20 in New York,
and United States Vice President Albert Gore will be present as
co-chairman of the meeting, Secretary of the Ukrainian State
Committee on Security and Defense Vladimir Gorbulin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Gorbulin said there still remains 150-210 tons of nuclear fuel
in the damaged fourth reactor following the 1986 nuclear
accident. One of the major tasks the Ukrainian government faced
was to rebuild the damaged sarcophagus around the ruined reactor.
</P>
<P>
Experts said it will cost around 750 million U.S. dollars to
repair the concrete shell.
</P>
<P>
To date, the Group of Seven industrial powers - Britain,
Canada, France, Germany, Italy, Japan and the United States - have
approved a 300 million dollars grant to help the project and the
European Union agreed to contribute 100 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian government itself will allocate years 150
million dollars for the project in the next seven years.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma is expected to raise the remaining 300 million dollars
at next week's donors'meeting.
</P>
<P>
Another Interfax news agency report said that during Kuchma's
stay in New York, the president will also discuss with
U.S. officials issues involving technology, chemical weapons and
the bilateral relationship. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
