<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cindy Brown Signs With WNBA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, November 14 (Xinhua) -- The WNBA announced on Friday
the signing of forward Cindy Brown to a contract to play during
the 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
Brown was a member of the 1988 U.S. women's Olympic basketball
team that won the gold medal in Seoul, South Korea. During the
1988 Olympics, she played in all five games for the U.S. team team
and averaged 8.0 points.
</P>
<P>
The 1988 Olympic team also included current WNBA players
Cynthia Cooper of the Houston Comets, Sacramento's Bridgette
Gordon, Charlotte's Vicky Bullett, New York's Teresa Weatherspoon
and Phoenix's Jennifer Gillom. Brown's signing brings the total
number of Olympians competing in the WNBA to 24.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very excited about playing for a first-class organization
like the WNBA," said Brown, "I look forward to the upcoming WNBA
season and helping to bring professional women's basketball to the
next level."
</P>
<P>
Brown currently is competing in France for US Valenciennes
Orchies and has also played for other professional teams in Italy,
Japan and Israel.
</P>
<P>
It has not yet been determined which WNBA team Brown will play
for in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Brown, from Oregon, graduated from Long Beach State University
in 1987. During her four-year career at Long Beach State, she led
the 49ers to four consecutive NCAA Tournament berths and the
school's first-ever Final Four apperance her senior year.
</P>
<P>
Brown holds the NCAA women's record for most points scored in a
game, with 60 against San Jose State University on February 16,
1987.
</P>
<P>
Last season, Brown wa a member of the American Basketball
League's Seattle Reign. During the regular season, she averaged
17.5 points, 8.3 rebounds and 2.6 steals per game and was chosen
to play in the inaugural ABL All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
"Cindy is a consistent scorer and an outstanding overall
player," said WNBA president Val Ackerman, "We are very happy that
she has joined the WNBA, and we know that WNBA fans will enjoy her
explosive offensive game." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
