<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Sign Planned Peace Treaty with Tribal Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 15 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government is
scheduled to hold the next and probably final round of talks with
the tribal rebels on Sunday, in a bid to finalize the
controversial peace agreement for the trouble-torn Chittagong Hill
Tracts (CHT).
</P>
<P>
After six rounds of secret talks since the Awami (people's)
League took power last June, the government has finally reached a
draft agreement with the Parbattya Chattagram Jana Sanghati
Samity, the political wing of the armed rebels.
</P>
<P>
Official sources could not confirm any date of signing of the
agreement but there is speculation that it may be signed any day
between November 16 and 21 if there are no fresh complications.
</P>
<P>
"Some minor issues were yet to be resolved but those could be
solved easily," said an official of the prime minister's office,
adding that the two sides have been centering on the control of
the local police, the local administration and its power over
land.
</P>
<P>
Other sources indicated that the agreement might be signed
after the three-nation Business Summit scheduled for November 23
with the participation of prime ministers from India, Pakistan and
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bangladeshi tribal refugees, crammed in six camps in
the Indian state of Tripura, will resume returning home on
November 21.
</P>
<P>
The planned peace agreement on the CHT has already come under
strong criticism by the main opposition Bangladesh Nationalist
Party (BNP), and its allies, including Jamaat-e-Islami, who say
the accord would jeopardize national sovereignty and territorial
integrity.
</P>
<P>
The BNP-led combined opposition of the CHT has called for a
dawn-to-dusk countrywide general strike on the day when the
agreement is signed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
