<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Government Committed to Rural Uplift: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 15 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government is
committed to improving the overall condition of the rural people
through the new four tiers of elected local government bodies, the
national news agency BSS reported here today.
</P>
<P>
This was stated by Zillur Rahman, minister of Local Government,
Rural Development and Cooperatives, while addressing a seminar on
"Strengthening Local Governance in Bangladesh" in Manikganj city
Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We do not want to make the rural people totally dependent on
the state machinery," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The rural people under the proposed system will incorporate
themselves in the local government bodies paying the way for
poverty alleviation, BSS quoted the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
The government agencies involved in the development process
will be made accountable and transparent to the common people
through enactment of law, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The local government bodies will ensure national development,
and will be governed by the rural people, the minister said,
adding they would never behave like carrier of the orders and
messages of the ruling elite.
</P>
<P>
He told the seminar that after completion of the on-going
township election, the village council election will be held in
February next.
</P>
<P>
All these endeavors are pointed towards ensuring the smooth
functioning of the local government system, he said, adding that
"people's leadership, welfare and economic emancipation will be
guaranteed and the system will be extended up to the grassroots
level."
</P>
<P>
The government is sincere in involving women in the democratic
process, because women, accounting for half of the population, can
contribute enormously to the national development, the minister
stressed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971115.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolia Decides on Economic Austerity Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, November 14 (Xinhua) -- Mongolia has decided on an
austerity policy to keep the stability of exchange rate of its
currency the tugrik and the momentum of economic development.
</P>
<P>
The policy is contained in the 1998 fundamental guiding
principle on Mongolia's economic and social development passed by
the Great Hural (parliament) on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the policy, Mongolia's gross domestic product
(GDP) in 1998 is to go up by 5.4 percent, with a deficit rate not
exceeding 8.6 percent of the GDP, inflation rate under 20 percent
and foreign reserves standing at more than 80 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia's economy continued a slow growth in the last 10
months, though the country had a good season in animal husbandry,
increased grain output and a 2.4-percent growth in its industrial
output value. Inflation rate in the period ran at 14.3 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
