<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Continue Allowing Ukrainian Steel in Duty Free </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, November 14 (Xinhua) -- The United States recently
decided to postpone investigation into Ukraine's alleged dumping
of steel and allow Ukrainian steel to enter the U.S. market duty
free until 2002, media here reported today.
</P>
<P>
The U.S, Department of Commerce imposed preliminary duties on
Ukrainian steel this summer after U.S. mills accused Ukrainian
steel makers of selling their products at dumping prices.
</P>
<P>
However, under the terms of a five-year agreement signed
recently, the U.S. has given Ukraine an annual duty-free quota of
158,000 tons of steel, a far cry from the 350,000 tons Ukraine
wanted.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government started levying duties of 100 percent and
177 percent respectively on Ukrainian mills after U.S. companies
complained last November.
</P>
<P>
With the duties imposed, the Ukrainian steel industry lost up
to 70 million U.S. dollars this year. Ukraine exported 572,000
tons of steel with an average price of 361 dollars per ton to the
U.S. in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
