<DOCNO> XIE19971115.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia, Europe Push Ahead Trade Facilitation Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 15 (Xinhua) -- The Second Asia-Europe
Business Forum (AEBF II) Friday urged the private sectors in Asia
and Europe to speed up their input into government initiatives
such as the Trade Facilitation Action Plan (TFAP).
</P>
<P>
The plan should be finalized early in order to allow the
governments of Asia-Europe Meeting (ASEM) countries to adopt it at
their meeting in London on April 3-4 next year, the forum said in
a chairman's statement released at the end of its two-day meeting
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The forum agreed that the priority areas suggested in the
framework for TFAP endorsed by economic ministers at their meeting
in September 1997 in Japan are generally commendable," said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
The forum called on governments to enhance their work in the
areas of government procurement, quarantine inspection, and
intellectual property rights.
</P>
<P>
Governments should ensure transparency, simplification,
availability and consistency of trade information, particularly
with regard to regulations, standards and other procedures related
to trade in goods and services with the objective of achieving
unified testing standards and acceptance of suppliers declarations
on conformity, the forum said.
</P>
<P>
It proposed the setting up of a data base on trade standards
and procedures of ASEM countries for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
The forum also pointed out that deregulation should be
encouraged in order to increase trade opportunities and joint
ventures in the field of goods and services between Asian and
European companies.
</P>
<P>
"Rules and regulations governing trade and trade related
activities for foreign firms should be made readily available,
applied effectively, consistently and in a non-discriminatory
manner," the forum said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
Also, the forum urged governments to proceed with early and
full implementation of the commitments undertaken in the Uruguay
Round of multilateral trade negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The priority should be given to tariff quotas and licenses,
simplification of customs procedures, transparency of relevant
laws and regulations, trading rights and distribution in local
markets, intellectual property rights, and standards testing and
certification, it said.
</P>
<P>
"Strengthening two-way trade flows in goods and services
between Asia and Europe is a major objective of the Asia-Europe
Business Forum," it said.
</P>
<P>
Describing its role in this respect, the forum said that it
will provide private sector input into government initiatives,
identify obstacles to trade activities and the solutions, find
opportunities for closer private sector cooperation, and support
efforts to strengthen the multilateral system embodied in the
World Trade Organization.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971115.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1.5 Million People Live in Slums in Dhaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 15 (Xinhua) -- There are 3,007 slums in Dhaka
metropolitan area with about 1.5 million slum-dwellers, the
independent United News of Bangladesh (UNB) reported here today.
</P>
<P>
Zillur Rahman, minister of local government, rural development
and cooperatives, quoted the statistics from the latest survey
made by the Urban Poverty Reduction Project while replying to a
slum-related question raised in the Parliament Thursday, UNB said.
</P>
<P>
The present government has no plan to rehabilitate the
slum-dwellers, the minister stated, adding that such a program can
be taken if the country gets necessary foreign assistance for the
purpose.
</P>
<P>
The minister told the Parliament that 130 slum families were
rehabilitated in City Palli in 1990 in order to ensure a
pollution-free environment in the capital.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the Dhaka City Corporation has been conducting a
project to improve the living standard of 31,000 people in 18
slums since 1991 with financial assistance from UNICEF and
technical assistance from the Local Government Engineering
Department, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The project includes drinking water supply, primary healthcare,
primary education and credit for self-employment, he said.
</P>
<P>
Dhaka, capital of Bangladesh, has a population of nine million.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971115.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Infectious Diseases Decline in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 15 (Xinhua) -- The incidence of major
infectious disceases has been declining in China in the past seven
years, an official with the Ministry of Public Health said.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Daily quoted Wang Zhao, department director in
charge of disease control with the Ministry of Public Health, as
saying that China has detected no polio cases caused by "wild
polio virus" since 1994.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening of a four-day national meeting on
communicable-diseases control and prevention, she said the country
registered 922 cholera cases, a drop of 81 percent from the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
More than 90 percent of new-borns in cities are now vaccinated
against hepatitis B, the average rate for rural areas is 42.5
percent, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
The hepatitis B antigen positive rate among children below 10
years old has dropped from around 10 percent in the early 1990s to
the current 1.19 percent.
</P>
<P>
She said, thanks to a sound anti-epidemic network, no serious
epidemics were reported after natural disasters such as flooding,
earthquake and drought.
</P>
<P>
All newly emerging and re-appearing communicable illnesses,
such as HIV/AIDS and tuberculosis, are under strict surveillance.
</P>
<P>
However, the official emphasised that this is no time for the
nation to rest on its laurels, adding more efforts will be needed
in the future to maintain this achievement and tackle new problems
brought by the newly appearing and re-emerging illnesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971115.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Explosions Damage 3 Transformers in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Three mysterious explosions at
a Ceylon Electricity Board (CEB) substation in Badulla, Uva
province, damaged three transformers Friday morning, reports
reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
The reports said the explosions in the early hours of Friday at
the station damaged three of the four transformers.
</P>
<P>
The nearly 40-year-old transformers were each valued at about
60,000 U.S. dollars, a senior official of the CEB was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the damage to the transformers has not been estimated
yet.
Investigation is underway.
</P>
<P>
The incident coincided with a fire caused by bomb blasts in a
thermal power station in Colombo Friday morning. Police have
confirmed that the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam was involved
in the Colombo power plant fire.  
</P>
</TEXT>
