<HEADLINE> Fodder Production Software Exports to US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 15 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing Resources Fodder
Group has announced plans to export its advanced fodder production
software series to the United States.
</P>
<P>
The group will become the first Chinese company to export this
particular type of highly specialized software to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
A Beijing accounting firm has appraised the value of the
copyrighted software series at 3.57 million yuan (410,000 US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The software package provides detailed instructions for
producing fodder for pigs, chickens, cows, sheep, fish and various
other species of animals.
</P>
<P>
The software determines the best composition and lowest
possible cost of fodder for specific species.
</P>
<P>
The software series is used extensively by China's large-scale
fodder production companies. The group has sold 600 software
packages since the series was introduced in early 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971115.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Gas Field in Northwest China Under Full Exploration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, November 15 (Xinhua) -- The Changqing Gas Field in
northwest China has entered full-scale exploration since the first
high-yield gas well was sunk in the field on June 22, 1989.
</P>
<P>
The field is situated in the Erdos Basin which sits on the
juncture of Shaanxi, Gansu, Shanxi provinces, and Ningxia Hui,
Inner Mongolia autonomous regions.
</P>
<P>
Over the past eight years, the Changqing Petroleum Prospecting
Administration, which is in charge of oil and gas prospecting and
development in the gas field, has spent over three billion yuan on
gas prospecting and has sunk 220 testing wells.
</P>
<P>
The gas field is proven to have gas reserves of 289.6 billion
cu m, and has a gas-bearing area totalling over 4,960 sq km.
</P>
<P>
Since 1991, the Changqing Petroleum Prospecting Administration
has invested 1.2 billion yuan in building 14 gas accumulation
stations, sinking 39 gas treatment wells, laying 450 km of
pipelines and building China's largest gas purification station,
with a gas accumulation capacity of three billion cu m.
</P>
<P>
The gas field, now with an annual capacity of 840 million cu m
of gas, started to supply gas to Xi'an, capital of northwest
China's Shaanxi Province, last June, and to Beijing last
September. By the end of October, it had produced 1.9 billion cu m
of gas.
</P>
<P>
Shi Xingquan, Director of the Changqing Petroleum Prospecting
Administration, pledged that his administration would work harder
to bring the volume of proven gas reserves from the present 289.6
billion cu m to 1,000 billion cu m by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
He is confident of realizing the goal as the Erdos Basin,
China's second largest after Tarim Basin, also in northwest
China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, has 4,170 billion cu m
of gas resources which account for over 10 percent of China's
total.
</P>
<P>
The gas field will form a production capacity of 5.5 billion cu
m of gas by the turn of this century and will further increase the
capacity to 10 billion cu m by the year of 2010.
</P>
<P>
According to him, two more pipelines, Shaanxi
(Qingbian)-Ningxia (Yinchuan) and Shaanxi(Qingbian)-Gansu
(Lanzhou) pipelines, will soon begin construction. It is expected
that the two pipelines will be finished and put into service in
1998 and 1999, respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
