<HEADLINE> Italy to Sharpen Competitiveness in Global Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, November 14 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto
Dini today offered up his recipe for sharpening the country's
competitive edge on the global market.
</P>
<P>
If the country is to maintain and bolster its competitiveness,
Dini said, it must adopt ever more efficient policies that promote
the effective interaction of Italy's political, economic and
social forces within a new reference framework shaped with the
help and mutual consent of both the public and the private sectors.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark when addressing a workshop held in Florence,
Italy, under the theme of "Free Trade and the World
Market: European Strategies."
</P>
<P>
"In a world of ever more liberalized trade, new results must be
reached within a framework that ensures full implementation of the
rules governing competition," Dini said.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that the World Trade Organization (WTO), which
has created an intergovernmental work group to give in-depth
attention to this issue, should play a fundamental role.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is co-organized by the European University
Institute and the Italian Foreign Trade Ministry.
</P>
<P>
All the ministers of the 15 European Union (EU) member states
responsible for trade policy participated in the meeting. Also
presented were Leon Brittan, vice president of the EU Commission
and Renato Ruggiero, director general of the WTO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
