<HEADLINE> Lipinski Leads Short Program in Lalique Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 14 (Xinhua) -- World champion Tara Lipinski
finished first in the short program at the Lalique Trophy
competition Friday, a step towards her first victory of the season.
</P>
<P>
Lipinski, 15, became the youngest women world champion when she
took the title at Lausanne, Switzerland last March.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Lipinski, with a height of 147 centimeters, hit all
the elements in her program including a solid triple lutz-double
loop combination for most scores of 5.6s and 5.7s.
</P>
<P>
Laetitia Hubert of France finished second with Krisztina Czacko
of Hungary third.
</P>
<P>
Chen Lu, the 1995 world champion, continued her comeback with a
fourth place. Her artistic marks challenged Lipinski in the 5.4
to 5.8 range.
</P>
<P>
The final free programs are on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Later in the men's program, American Todd Eldredge crashed and
sprained his shoulder in a bad fall.
</P>
<P>
Russians Yelena Berezhzaya and Anton Sikharulidze edged world
champions Mandy Woetzel and Ingo Steuer of Germany in the short
pairs program.
</P>
<P>
The Lalique Trophy event is one of the six Grand Prix meets
leading to the Champion Series final slated in Munich on December
19-21. 
</P>
</TEXT>
