<HEADLINE> Russia Agrees to Drop Import Tax on Ukrainian Sugar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, November 14 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian coffers will see a
sweeter year in 1998 as Moscow agreed Friday to drop a 25 percent
import tax on Ukrainian sugar.
</P>
<P>
However, under the deal reached here, Moscow will impose an
annual quota of 60,000 tons on imports of Ukrainian sugar.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed on a list of Russian commodities that
would enter the Ukrainian market duty-free.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine is the largest sugar producer among the former Soviet
republics. Its sugar, used to sweeten the whole Soviet Union, was
forced out of the Russian market when Moscow announced a
25-percent import tax last May, a heavy blow to its fragile
economy.
</P>
<P>
Kiev, in retaliation, decided to levy value-added taxes on
Russian exports to Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
As a result, trade volume between the neighbors plummeted in
the past few months.
</P>
<P>
Observers say export of 60,000 tons of sugar will not help Kiev
much because Ukraine used to sell Moscow more than one million
tons annually.
</P>
<P>
Trade is expected to remain a main topic during Ukrainian
President Leonid Kuchma's visit to Russia from November 16 to 17.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
