<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Mexico Pledge More Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
and visiting Mexican President Ernest Zedillo signed here today a
joint declaration for more cooperation between their two countries.
</P>
<P>
"We met to carry forward the mature partnership between our two
governments, marked by mutual respect...to continue our personal
contacts in order to spur further cooperation on issues of vital
importance to our citizens," the two leaders said in the joint
declaration.
</P>
<P>
The joint declaration, signed after a meeting between the two
presidents at the White House, said that they agreed to cooperate
in talks on climate change, border and drug control, macroeconomic
issues, trade and environment.
</P>
<P>
Two-way trade between the U.S. and Mexico has doubled since the
North American Free Trade Agreement came into effect in 1994 and
will total 165 billion U.S. dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
Mexico, which has been the second largest export market for
U.S. goods ahead of Japan, was one of the countries that is
considered by the U.S. as vitally important to its long-term
prosperity and security.
</P>
<P>
"We are convinced that two neighbors and partners, like the
U.S. and Mexico, can address even the most complex issues through
mutual respect, constructive dialogue and cooperation," the two
leaders announced.
</P>
<P>
The increased trade between the two countries and across the
2800 kilometer border have brought many problems.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents expressed concern about food safety and
agreed to establish a way to ensure food products traded between
their countries were safe.
</P>
<P>
"We also agreed on the need to further bolster efforts to
reduce the demand for illicit drugs, as part of a comprehensive
approach to anti-narcotics cooperation," they said.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the two countries need "effective action
against drug corruption on both sides of the border."
</P>
<P>
On climate change, they said they agreed that developed
countries like the U.S. must lead by reducing emissions of
green-house gases and Mexico, like other developing countries,
"should be willing to participate in an approach global regime."
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the two presidents also attended a signing
ceremony of a convention on stemming the illicit firearms signed
by 29 members of the Organization of American States (OAS).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
