<HEADLINE> Scientists Turn West Lake Silt Into Fertilizer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese technicians have
successfully used silt in the West Lake of Hangzhou City in east
China's Zhejiang Province to produce organic composite fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
Large-scale experiment indicated that the yield of rice
cultivated with the application of silt-turned fertilizer shot up
at least 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Silt in the lake is 0.6 meters thick while water depth averages
only 1.59 meters.
</P>
<P>
Starting from 1996, the Zhejiang Yinshida Corporation began to
develop West Lake silt.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Heng, General Manager of the company, said, with support
from the State Science and Technology Commission, a pilot plant
has been built and it can process 50,000 cubic meters of lake silt
and produce 60,000 tons of organic composite fertilizer annually
starting from next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
