<HEADLINE> Police Say 3 Tamil Rebels Had Entered Power Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Three rebels of the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) had sneaked into a power plant and
planted bombs onto four oil tanks, causing explosion and fire to
the plant in Colombo, police said here today.
</P>
<P>
Police said initial investigations have revealed that the
terrorists had entered the security zone of the power station from
its railway line side by cutting barbed wire entanglements early
Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
The Tigers fixed a total of ten magnetic explosive devices onto
four diesel tanks after they entered the plant, police said.
</P>
<P>
Security personnel also found two leaflets in Tamil giving
instructions as to how to use the explosive devices.
</P>
<P>
Fire broke out following the explosion of the devices at around
5 o'clock local time Friday at the biggest thermal power plant in
Sri Lanka, which was built in 1963 and expanded thereafter.
</P>
<P>
The fire was brought under control within 30 minutes and the
tanks sustained minor damages, according to the authorities.
</P>
<P>
Friday's power plant fire was the latest attempt by the LTTE to
create chaos in the capital city Colombo.
</P>
<P>
Last month, a truck bomb exploded in the business center of
Colombo, shocking economic nerves of the country as 18 people were
killed, 100 more others wounded and many landmarks damaged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
