<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Launch Another 2 Satellites Next Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 15 (Xinhua) -- China will launch an improved
model of Long March-2-III rocket loading with two iridium
satellites owned by US-based Motorola Inc during the first week of
December, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
It will be the 11th launch this year by the China Academy of
Launch Vehicle Technology, said Li Jianzhong, director of the
academy, China's rocket researcher and developer.
</P>
<P>
The ten previous successful launches of satellites and other
objects marked this memorable year, which has seen the highest
success rate of 100 percent, Li said at a press conference
yesterday celebrating the academy's 40th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the academy is considering listing itself on the
stock market as part of the efforts to promote the development of
launch vehicles.
</P>
<P>
According to the director, it is trying to shorten the research
and developing periods of launch vehicles as it works to develop a
mature rocket-production industry.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Li added, his academy is strengthening
quality control to ensure and enhance the stability of its rocket.
</P>
<P>
In the past 40 years the academy has developed a series of Long
March launch vehicles that can meet the requirements of most
launches and has occupied a share of the world market of launch
services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
