<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Asks UN to Buy More Thai Goods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 15 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Commerce Ministry has
asked the United Nations to order more Thai products, as part of
the country's campaign to earn more foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
UN purchasing agents met Friday with several Thai manufacturers
to discuss the possibility of Thai goods being procured by UN
agencies for third countries, according to the local press today.
</P>
<P>
The UN is a huge buyer, spending about 3.5 billion U.S. dollars
worldwide last year. Thailand's share of the total was about 34
million dollars, slightly less than 1 percent, Sanit Worapanya,
director general of the Export Promotion Department of the
Commerce Ministry, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Sanit suggested that Thai exporters register their companies
with the IN office.
</P>
<P>
Potential products for Thailand to sell to the UN include rice,
canned seafood, sugar, apparel, plastic products, drugs and
services.  
</P>
</TEXT>
