<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT November 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- James D. Wolfensohn, President of the World Bank
Friday announced the appointment of Shengman Zhang (Chinese) as
Managing Director and Corporate Secretary of the World Bank Group.
</P>
<P>
Zhang will be responsible for providing corporate management
and oversight in a number of key areas. In the process, he will
help take a more strategic and coherent approach to a number of
institution-wide functions which play a critical role in
supporting the operations of the World Bank Group.
</P>
<P>
Zhang, a Chinese national was chosen by Wolfensohn as his vice
president at the end of 1995, six months after he took up the
World Bank president.
</P>
<P>
Zhang is the first Chinese who has been promoted to the
high-ranking position in the World Bank's over 50 years of history.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- President Bill Clinton argued for his sending the
aircraft carrier George Washington to the Persian Gulf, saying it
was a "prudent measure" for any contingency, which might occur
amid rising tension with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"I have ordered today the aircraft carrier George Washington to
the region as a prudent measure to help assure that we have the
forces we need for any contingency," the president told reporters
at a White House briefing Friday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Friday morning, Clinton announced the move during a
photo session with Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
ATHENS -- Washington should pressure Ankara into cooperating
towards resolving the protracted Cyprus problem, said Greek
Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after briefing Greek President Costis
Stephanopoulos on recent foreign policy developments, Pangalos
said that the initiative by U.S. presidential envoy on the Cyprus
issue, Richard Holbrooke, was important as far as the U.S.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Richard Butler, chief weapons inspector of the
United Nations, said Friday he believed U.N. inspectors, now
pulled out of Iraq, would be back to discharge their duties again.
</P>
<P>
"I refuse to believe that the international community is simply
going to walk away from the very large problem that is presented
by Iraq's weapons of mass destruction," he said in an interview
with CNN. "We'll have to be back, in one way or another, and as
soon as possible."
</P>
<P>
Six American inspectors of the U.N. weapons inspection teams
left Iraq late Thursday following Baghdad's order of their
expulsion. And the other 68 U.N. team members also flew out of
Iraq Friday to Bahrein under the order of Butler in protest to
Iraq's expulsion of the Americans.
</P>
<P>
MOGADISHU -- Apart from human and livestock fatalities, the
floods that hit seven regions of southern Somalia are also
bringing about starvation and famine in many flood-besieged
villages and towns.
</P>
<P>
In Gedo, Middle Jubba, Lower Jubba, Middle Shabelle, Hiran, Bay
and Bakol regions of southern Somalia, life has become difficult
for hundreds of thousands of people in the flood affected towns
and villages as the food prices rose to five folds.
</P>
<P>
NAGOYA -- Governor of Japan's Aichi Prefecture Leigi Suzuki
Friday extended his whole-hearted welcome to Chinese Premier Li
Peng who arrived here Friday afternoon to continue his visit to
Japan.
</P>
<P>
At a banquet held in honor of the Chinese premier, Suzuki said
exchanges between Aichi Prefecture and China could be traced to a
long time ago.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON, -- Amid rising tensions with Iraq after Baghdad
expelled American inspectors, U.S. President Bill Clinton Friday
ordered the aircraft carrier George Washington to leave the
Mediterranean for the Persian Gulf to join the aircraft carrier
Nimitz, already deployed there.
</P>
<P>
"I thought it was appropriate under the circumstances," Clinton
said during a photo session with Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the United Nations made the correct decision in
withdrawing all the U.N. weapons inspectors in protest against
President Saddam Hussein's order to expel American inspectors
within the U.N. weapons inspection teams.
</P>
<P>
PYONGYANG -- A Japanese official delegation left Pyongyang for
home Thursday after reaching an agreement with the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) on resuming normalization talks,
reported the Central Korean News Agency (KCNA).
</P>
<P>
Both sides have expressed the wish to resume the talks as soon
as possible, said the official KCNA. Previous talks collapsed in
1992.
</P>
<P>
Japanese and DPRK people can advance together toward the future
while promoting understanding of each other, said Yoshiro Mori,
head of the delegation composed of the Japanese tripartite ruling
bloc, on the eve of his departure.
</P>
<P>
The talks between the ruling parties of the two countries will
provide a good opportunity for deepening understanding of the two
peoples and improving DPRK-Japanese relations, said Kim Yanggon, a
senior official of the DPRK's Workers' Party of Korea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
