<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Model of World's First Seismograph on Display in South China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, November 15 (Xinhua) -- A replica of an ancient
seismograph invented by Chinese scientist Zhang Heng is on display
in the Guangdong Provicial Museum in Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
Technicians from Henan province produced a duplicate of the
2.96-meter high, 2.68-meter in diameter device that is shaped like
a wine vessel.
</P>
<P>
According to the State Seismology Bureau, it is similar in
appearance, structure, and function to a description provided by
historical documents.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Heng made the original in A.D. 132, and his device
monitored an earthquake 854 kilometers away in A.D. 138.
</P>
<P>
But, the scientist only worked on a simple description of his
invention in 196 characters. So, for hundreds of years, inventors
in many countries have tried to duplicate the seismograph, but its
complex internal structure defeated them.
</P>
<P>
After the exhibition here, a Guangzhou auction house will
auction the machine off in December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
