<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Issues Regulations on Commodity Shows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 15 (Xinhua) -- The State Administration for
Industry and Commerce has issued the Administrative Rules on
Commodity Exhibitions, which will go into effect on January 1,
1998.
</P>
<P>
It stipulates that those who plan to sponsor such a show should
apply for a certificate from local industrial and commercial
authorities, before they launch advertisements to invite
participants.
</P>
<P>
Violators could be fined at most 5,000 yuan and advertisers
concerned should be also fined in accordance to the rules.
</P>
<P>
Co-exhibitors can apply for licence through an intermediary
exhibition service organization, it says.
</P>
<P>
The document also stresses that the autorities must make the
decision within 15 days on receiving the application, and issue
certificates or give reasons for refusal in written form.
</P>
<P>
Those who fabricate, alter, lease or transfer their
certificates will be also fined within a limit of 30,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
In addition, without approval from the State Council, no
exhibition should use the word "China" or "national", it says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
