<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Americans Abroad Warned of Retaliation on CIA Shooter Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department
today warned American citizens abroad that they could be targets
for retaliation after a U.S. jury recommended to sentence to death
a Pakistani for killing two CIA officers in 1993.
</P>
<P>
It was the second such warning since Mir Aimal Kasi was
convicted of murder Monday by the same jury in Fairfax, Virginia.
</P>
<P>
"The Department advises Americans traveling abroad that the
potential exists for retaliation by Kasi's sympathizers against
American interests," the State Department said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"While we have no specific threat information, American
citizens traveling abroad should pay close attention to their
personal security practices overseas in light of the potential
threat," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
After Kasi's conviction, four Americans were shot dead in
Karachi, Pakistan. Pakistani officials and some U.S. lawmakers
said the killings were apparently retaliation for the conviction
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Kasi, 33, was convicted of shooting dead two CIA officers and
wounding three others outside the main gate of the Central
Intelligence Agency in Langley, Virginia, on January 25, 1993.
</P>
<P>
Kasi returned to his native Pakistan after the shooting.
Following four and a half years of manhunt, the U.S. Federal
Bureau of Investigation (FBI) tracked him to a Pakistani hotel and
arrested him in June, then brought him to the United States.
</P>
<P>
The 12-member Fairfax County jury made the death penalty
recommendation today. But the judge is expected to pronounce the
final sentence on January 23. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
