<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Cataract Sufferers Getting International Assistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, November 15 (Xinhua) -- A four-year-old internationally
project has helped more than 6,000 farmers, herdsmen, urbanites,
workers and officials suffering from cataracts in the Tibet
Autonomous Region recover their eyesight.
</P>
<P>
The oldest of the patients is 106, and youngest, three months
old.
</P>
<P>
Government departments have put 36 million yuan (4.5 million US
dollars) into the program, and according to the Aid Tibet
Development Fundation (ATDF) in the capital city, Lhasa, in the
third quarter of this year, 2,500 cataract patients underwent free
eye surgery.
</P>
<P>
The region has the highest incidence of cataract disease in
China, because of its high altitude, long periods of sunshine,
strong ultraviolet rays, and brightness from the snow in winter.
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, ATDF has invited people from foreign
non-governmental charitable organizations to operate free of
charge on local cataract sufferers. The project has gotten help
from the US SEVA Foundation, the Nepal Eye Program, the Foundation
Eye-Care Himalaya of the Netherlands, and Germany's Christofle
Blindness Mission.
</P>
<P>
ATDF and SEVA have signed an agreement to set up an eye
treatment center in Lhasa. The center will also be responsible for
training medical workers.
</P>
<P>
ATDF, Lhasa's first non-governmental charitable organization,
was established ten years ago. Its aim is to make better use of
foreign assistance to speed up the economic and social development
of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
ATDF has raised over 100 million yuan (12.5 million US dollars)
and launched more than 360 assistance projects.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
