<DOCNO> XIE19971115.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Chief Comes to Review Philippine Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Managing Director Michel
Camdessus of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) is arriving
here today from Bangkok to review the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus is on the last leg of his Southeast Asia tour to
check on the region's currency turmoil. He has been to Jakarta,
Singapore and Kuala Lumpur.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus is expected to discuss with President Fidel Ramos and
government officials the status of the Philippine economy and the
exit of the country from the IMF program.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the IMF has asked the Philippines to "be more
realistic" and reduce its 1998 economic growth target to a range
of four to five percent from the projected 6.5 to 7.5 percent,
saying a higher growth target may result in bigger budget deficit
and higher interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Manila last month slashed its 1997 growth target by two
percentage points to between 5.5 and 6 percent as a result of the
currency crisis sweeping the region.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government is hoping to put its economic house
in order to be able to graduate from 35 years of IMF tutelage by
the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
However, the scheduled exit was put in doubt after the
country's Supreme Court declared the oil deregulation law
"unconstitutional" a couple of days ago. The law was one of the
three parts of a program which the Philippines must complete
before quitting the IMF.
</P>
<P>
Finance Secretary Roberto de Ocampo said the currency situation
in the country is stabilizing even when the country maintains its
plan of exiting from the IMF.
</P>
<P>
"We have not needed an IMF assistance package. In fact, we are
due to exit from the IMF while others are entering," he said.
</P>
<P>
During the trip to Manila, Camdessus will also discuss the
setting up of an Asia fund to help battle the currency crisis.
President Ramos said the country has been all set to push for the
fund despite the IMF's opposition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
