<HEADLINE> House Committee Begins Investigating Influential Congressman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 14 (Xinhua) -- The ethics committee of the
U.S. House of Representatives Friday began investigating
Pennsylvania Representative Bud Shuster, an influential Republican
whose Transportation Committee authorizes highway and mass transit
programs affecting every state.
</P>
<P>
The move was based on a complaint challenging the propriety of
Shuster's personal and professional ties with Ann Eppard, a
transportation lobbyist who was his congressional chief of staff
for 22 years.
</P>
<P>
Under his leadership, Congress this week completed action on a
9.7 billion-dollar bill that will keep state highway programs
operating for another six months.
</P>
<P>
"I'm pleased that the committee is moving expeditiously. This
is the proper procedure," Shuster said.
</P>
<P>
Ann Eppard Associates, specializing in issues before Shuster's
committee, took in 1.1 million dollars from 17 clients in 1996,
House records show. Her firm had 23 active clients this year and
took in 740,000 dollars in the first six months.
</P>
<P>
Eleven clients signed up in 1997, citing the new highway bill
as a subject matter for her lobbying.
</P>
<P>
Shuster last year called the complaint by the private
Congressional Accountability Project a "smear campaign" and "a
transparent attempt to influence" his 1996 re-election campaign.
The watchdog organization was founded by congressional critic
Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
Eppard also serves as assistant treasurer for his campaign and
has provided transportation for him. She receives a monthly
consulting fee for her campaign work and has helped him raise 1.7
million dollars since 1995.
</P>
<P>
The ethics complaint grew out of Shuster's disclosure that he
and his family have used Eppard's residence for overnight lodging
many times. Critics say the practice violates a ban on gifts.
Shuster and Eppard say the arrangement is legal because of their
longtime friendship.
</P>
<P>
Investigators have looked into allegations that Shuster and
Eppard used campaign funds for personal use and that business
deals were made with Eppard's son, Ralph, to win Shuster's help in
settling the property disputes, according to reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
