<HEADLINE> Coastal and Border Areas of China Get More Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 15 (Xinhua) -- China's coastal and border
provinces, municipalities, and autonomous regions saw 12,801
foreign-funded projects set up in the January-September period of
this year, the Shanghai Statistics Bureau reports.
</P>
<P>
They involve 31.59 billion US dollars of contractual
investment, with 27.79 billion U.S. dollars having been utilized.
</P>
<P>
The provinces of Guangdong, Fujian, and Jiangsu were the top
three places for foreign-funded projects, accounting for 46
percent of the total in 14 areas.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong and Jiangsu, and the city of Shanghai used 56 percent
of the total overseas investment of the 14 areas and were the top
three in the sector.
</P>
<P>
Foreign-funded projects in Jiangsu and Fujian provinces
increased by more than 20 percent over the same period of last
year, while foreign funds used by Yunnan province were 1.3 times
the 1996 figure.
</P>
<P>
The 14 coastal and border areas studied are the port city of
Tianjin, Shanghai, the provinces of Liaoning, Heilongjiang,
Jiangsu, Zhejiang, Fujian, Shandong, Guangdong, Hainan, and
Yunnan, and the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region and Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
