<HEADLINE> U.S. Army Official Resigns over Marine Remarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Assistant Army
Secretary Sara Lister resigned today over her recent public
comments that Marines were "extremists" and "dangerous," the
Pentagon announced.
</P>
<P>
"Her resignation was submitted, accepted, and I think the
matter is over," Defense Secretary William Cohen told reporters at
the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
Lister had apologized to the Marine Corps' commanding general,
but angry members of Congress on Thursday demanded her immediate
resignation.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Army said Lister thanked President
Bill Clinton and the Secretary of the Army for her opportunity to
serve the country and the Army.
</P>
<P>
Army Secretary Togo West said that "Lister has served soldiers,
civilians and their families with great dedication; however, we
certainly understand and respect her decision."
</P>
<P>
Lister, the Army's assistant secretary for manpower and reserve
affairs, made the comments on October 26 at a conference in
Baltimore sponsored by Harvard University's Institute for
Strategic Studies.
</P>
<P>
"I think the Army is much more connected to society than the
Marines," Lister said. "The Marines are extremists. Whenever you
have extremists, you've got some risks of total disconnection with
society. And that's a little dangerous," she added.
</P>
<P>
Marine Corps Commandant Gen. Charles Krulak said that Lister's
remarks had dismissed "222 years of sacrifice and dedication" of
the Marines.
</P>
<P>
House Speaker Newt Gingrich wrote to President Clinton calling
for her immediate dismissal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
