<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developmental Retardation of Obese Children Studied in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, November 15 (Xinhua) -- A study at No. four Hospital of
Harbin, the capital of northeast China's Heilongjiang province,
has shown that the accumulation of fat in the pituitary can cause
developmental retardation in obese children during puberty.
</P>
<P>
Around 10 percent of the corpulent children studied showed
developmental disturbances. The survey also shows that their
posterior pituitary gland was less dense than that of normal
children, hindering the secretion of a gonad stimulating hormone
during puberty and affecting the development of the sex organs.
</P>
<P>
So, researchers develped a "Degreasing Therapy" that involves
the use of medicines and a changed lifestyle. One part of the
therapy is the use of an enema to stimulate the development of
external genital organs and the prostate, and Chinese medicines
are used to reduce their weight and recover the normal functioning
of the pituitary gland.
</P>
<P>
"It is just not enough to take medicine. The most important
thing is to change corpulent children's lazy habits," says
Prof. Li Jiqi, a member of the China Sex Science Association.
</P>
<P>
Researchers also suggested a low-sugar, low-salt, high-protein,
and vitamin-rich diet for obese children. Clinical studies using
the therapy on 1,000 children have had good results, with 70
percent of them increasing development of the genital organs and
losing a great deal of weight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
