<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Rebound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, November 14 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street rose
sharply today as a tame inflation reading and a strong showing on
most foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average rose nearly 84.72 points to
7,572.48, erasing the remaining damage from Wednesday's 157-point
slide.
</P>
<P>
Broader indicators also posted sizable gains, led by the
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 2-to-1 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where NYSE volume totaled 634.78
million shares as against 642.34 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 11.69 to 928.35, and
the NYSE composite index rose 5.37 to 486.06.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 25.90 to 1,583.64, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index rose 5.76 to 672.62.
</P>
<P>
With key markets such as Hong Kong and Brazil rebounding
sharply today, Wall Street shrugged off another rough day in
Tokyo, where its benchmark Nikkei index has fallen 11.5 percent,
in less than three weeks.
</P>
<P>
U.S. stocks also drew a boost today from domestic economic
reports.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department reported this morning that prices paid for
finished goods to producers such as food processing plants and auto
factories inched just 0.1 percent higher. That follows a sharp 0.5
percent jump in September and a moderate 0.3 percent rise in
August.
</P>
<P>
Retail sales, meanwhile, fell 0.2 percent in October following
a 0.1 percent decline in September, the Commerce Department said.
</P>
</TEXT>
