<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Japanese Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Japanese newspapers today.
</P>
<P>
Asahi, Mainichi:
</P>
<P>
-- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto vowed Friday to
break up the postal ministry as one part of the proposed
administrative reform.
</P>
<P>
Mainichi:
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. President Bill Clinton on Friday ordered the aircraft
carrier George Washington to leave the Mediterranean for the
Persian Gulf amid rising tensions with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Yomiuri:
</P>
<P>
-- The U.N. Security Council issued a statement Thursday,
denouncing Iraq for expelling American inspectors on the
U.N. weapons inspection team working in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Asahi, Yomiuri, Mainichi, Nihon Keizai:
</P>
<P>
-- Concern over Japan's financial system and the sluggish
economy triggered selling of bank and securities stocks on the
Tokyo Stock Exchange, briefly sending the key Nikkei index below
15,000 on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
