<HEADLINE> U.S. Jury Recommends Death for Pakistani in CIA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 14 (Xinhua) -- A United States jury today
decided Mir Aimal Kasi, a Pakistani, should get the death penalty
for killing two CIA employees in a shooting rampage outside the
spy agency's headquarters near Washington, D.C. in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The decision by the Fairfax County jury, which convicted Kasi
on Monday, is only a recommendation, but Virginia judges generally
abide by such decisions.
</P>
<P>
The judge is expected to pronounce the final sentence on
January 23.
</P>
<P>
It took the panel less than seven hours. Kasi showed no emotion
as the verdict was read.
</P>
<P>
Kasi, 33, was found guilty of killing Frank Darling, 28, and
another CIA employee, Lansing Bennett, 66, on January 25, 1993. In
the shootings, two other CIA employees and another person were
wounded.
</P>
<P>
Kasi returned his native Pakistan after the shooting. Following
four and a half years of manhunt, the U.S. Federal Bureau of
Investigation (FBI) tracked him to a Pakistani hotel and arrested
him in June, then brought him to the United States.
</P>
<P>
The jury's decision came two days after four Americans were
shot to death in Karachi, Pakistan, that U.S. lawmakers said was
apparently retaliation for the conviction on Monday.
</P>
<P>
A group that claimed responsibility for the killings threatened
more attacks if Kasi was sentenced to death, according to reports
from Pakistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
