<HEADLINE> NZ First Fails to Decide Whether to Stay in Govt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, November 15 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand First party
 failed this morning to decide whether to stay in the coalition
Government, Radio NZ Reported.
</P>
<P>
Party leader Winston Peters was due to announce his party's
decision on whether to stay in the future government led by new
National Party leader Jenny Shipley who replaced Jim Bolger early
this month.
</P>
<P>
NZ First is now having its annual convention in the South
Island city of Christchurch. Peters told delegates that the party
executive and caucus will meet separately tomorrow for further
talks on the decision.
</P>
<P>
The report also said Peters approached the Labor Party last
night on the possibility that NZ First supported a Labor
government if Labor agreed to the 5 billion-dollar (3.1 billion
U.S. dollar) extra spending and tax cuts contained in the
coalition agreement with National.
</P>
<P>
But Labor leader Helen Clark had turned down the offer, saying
that it would not be credible for Labor to form a government on NZ
First terms. She said there should be an early election.  
</P>
</TEXT>
