<HEADLINE> Greece Urges U.S. to Pressure Turkey on Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, November 14 (Xinhua) -- Washington should pressure
Ankara into cooperating towards resolving the protracted Cyprus
problem, said Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after briefing Greek President Costis
Stephanopoulos on recent foreign policy developments, Pangalos
said that the initiative by U.S. presidential envoy on the Cyprus
issue, Richard Holbrooke, was important as far as the U. S.
undertook by all means at their disposal to pressure Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. could exert pressure by means of the military supplies
it gave Turkey and which were used in Cyprus, he said, adding
that Washington could limit those supplies or enforce a ban on
their use on the Aegean coast of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on criticism by the U.S. envoy that the European
Union (EU) had not undertaken any initiatives on the Cyprus issue,
he said that any effort by the EU to find a solution did not
require an "American mediator." "We can do this by ourselves," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been unofficially partitioned since 1974 when
Turkish troops took control of its northern third following an
abortive coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
