<HEADLINE> American Nations Sign Convention Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 14 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-nine members of the
Organization of the American States (OAS) today signed a
convention against the illicit manufacturing and trafficking of
guns, ammunition and explosives.
</P>
<P>
A signing ceremony, which took place at the headquarters of
OAS in Washington, was attended by U.S. President Bill Clinton
and Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
The convention is aimed at stemming the illicit manufacturing
of, and trafficking in firearms, ammunition, explosives and other
related materials.
</P>
<P>
"Gun trafficking is an issue of national security for our
governments, and a matter of neighborhood for all of us in the
Americas," Clinton said at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the document, Clinton added, shows that
countries on the West Hemisphere "are speaking with one voice,
acting with on conviction and leading toward one goal: to stem the
illegal flow of guns, ammunition and explosives in our hemisphere."
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that the new treaty will not affect the
lawful sale, ownership or use of guns.
</P>
<P>
Zedillo, who arrived here for a state visit on Thursday,
praised the U.S. and other OAS members for their support for his
proposal raised by him last year on the creation of the treaty.
</P>
<P>
"The most promising approach to confronting drug trafficking
and organized crime is an integrated strategy designed to respect
the sovereignty of each country and capable of taking full
advantage of the multilateral mechanisms that the international
community has at its disposal," said Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony, OAS Secretary General Cesar Gaviria
called the convention a "powerful tool" that will help governments
protect "the people who walk down our streets and the children who
play in our parks." 
</P>
</TEXT>
