<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Puts Gas Supply on Ration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 14 (Xinhua) -- Iraq today decided to ration
gas supply around the country starting Saturday in the face of
possible military actions taken by the U.S. and Britain.
</P>
<P>
The decision, made by the Oil Ministry, was announced on TV
Friday evening. The ministry cited swelling crowds and long queues
in gas stations as the reason for the latest rationing.
</P>
<P>
Under the new regulations, gas supply to a private car will be
curtailed to 40 liters for every four days while taxi and minibus
can get only twice as much during the same time span.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe this is a step taken by the Baghdad
government to prepare itself for a possible military showdown with
the U.S., which has ordered its aircraft carrier George Washington
to join another one USS Nimitz in the Persian Gulf for
"contingencies."
</P>
<P>
Iraq has vowed to shoot down any U.S. plane overflying Iraq on
inspection missions and refused to back down on its demands that
the seven-year-old sanctions be lifted in its standoff with the
U.S. and the U.N. Special Commission monitoring weapons'
eliminations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
