<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: Second Carrier to Gulf a "Prudent Measure" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 14 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton
argued for his sending the aircraft carrier George Washington to
the Persian Gulf, saying it was a "prudent measure" for any
contingency, which might occur amid rising tension with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"I have ordered today the aircraft carrier George Washington
to the region as a prudent measure to help assure that we have
the forces we need for any contingency," the president told
reporters at a White House briefing.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this morning, Clinton announced the move during a
photo session with Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo. He said
that "it was appropriate under the circumstances" to order the
George Washington from Mediterranean to the Gulf to join
another aircraft carrier Nimitz, already deployed there.
</P>
<P>
The arrival of the second carrier, expected about a week
later, would double the number of American Navy warplanes in the
Gulf, putting some 100 combat aircraft and another 50 support
aircraft in the region.
</P>
<P>
On its way to the Persian Gulf, the George Washington will be
accompanied by the USS Annapolis, an attack submarine, the
destroyer USS Carney and the cruiser USS Normandy.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the George Washington, the Pentagon also is
considering sending F-117 stealth fighters, and other Air Force
warplanes to the region as a major military buildup, some
officials said after the announcement of the dispatch of the
second carrier.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the United States would continue on diplomatic
front to impose pressure on Iraqi President Saddam Hussein so
that he could be forced to reverse his policy toward U.N.
weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
"The United States will work intensively with our allies and
our friends in the region and around the world to convince Iraq
to comply with the will of the international community as
expressed in the United nations resolution," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton supported U-2 mission under U.N. order to fly over
Iraq next week, because "without inspectors on the ground, it is
more important than ever to monitor events from the air."
</P>
</TEXT>
