<HEADLINE> Supporters to Keep Pushing Civil Rights Nomination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 14 (Xinhua) -- While the hope for Bill
Lann Lee holding the nation's top civil rights job depends on
President Bill Clinton's willingness to resubmit his nomination
and the will of his backers to fight for it, Lee's top Senate foe
Friday asked Clinton to send the Senate a new nominee.
</P>
<P>
"I think it's a loser for them," Senate Judiciary Committee
Chairman Orrin Hatch, Republican from Utah, said.
</P>
<P>
Hatch said the Senate late Thursday returned the nomination of
the Chinese-American civil rights lawyer to the White House after
Democrats failed earlier in the day to win enough votes to send it
to the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
Among its options, the White House could send up a new nominee
who would draw less criticism from Republicans opposed to Lee's
support of affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also could put Lee in the job on an interim basis, with
Congress adjourned for winter recess.
</P>
<P>
"I don't care what he does. At this point, it's dead," Hatch
said of the Lee nomination. He suggested Clinton "find somebody
for this position who will build a consensus."
</P>
<P>
Supporters want the White House to resubmit Lee because they
intend to intensify efforts to build grassroots support for a full
Senate vote.
</P>
<P>
Democrats blocked a Senate Judiciary Committee vote Thursday
that would have killed the nomination. Hatch, rather than leave
the nomination in limbo, had the nomination returned to the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
But Clint Bolick, vice president of the Institute for Justice,
who has led the opposition to Lee, said, "Clinton should withdraw
the nomination."
</P>
<P>
Hatch and other critics of affirmative action say Lee is wrong
for the job and that his support of such efforts will cloud his
judgment. Hatch also disagrees with the administration in its
support for affirmative action. 
</P>
</TEXT>
